commit_message:
Add openstack_user_domain to assertion

Currently, a keystone IdP does not provide the domain of the user
when generating SAML assertions. Since it is possible to have two
users with the same username but in different domains, this patch
adds an additional attribute called "openstack_user_domain"
in the assertion to identify the domain of the user.

Closes-Bug: 1442787
bp assertion-extra-attributes

Change-Id: I65d5c02c0a21f4d4c1b54f8aa56e27950d20badd

Does this need backporting to stable/kilo branch ?'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-05 17:07:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This is interesting, it suggests that the fsync will accept an fd that has fileno() method. Note that only the final call fails. So maybe there wan't a bug after all? (I need to go find and read some source code to be sure)

  >>> import swift.obj.diskfile as df
>>> fd = open('junk','wb')
>>> df.fsync(fd.fileno())
>>> df.fsync(fd)
>>> df.fsync('junk')
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "swift/common/utils.py", line 633, in fsync
    os.fsync(fd)
TypeError: argument must be an int, or have a fileno() method.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2015-05-05 17:09:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

No, I don't want to backport this"}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-05 17:27:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

From the docs:
https://docs.python.org/2/library/fcntl.html

"All functions in this module take a file descriptor fd as their first argument. This can be an integer file descriptor, such as returned by sys.stdin.fileno(), or a file object, such as sys.stdin itself, which provides a fileno() which returns a genuine file descriptor."

So no bug. But I still like the change because it makes our calls to fsync consistent.'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-05-06 06:00:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks acoles!

https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/2.7/Modules/posixmodule.c#L858'}]

swift.common.utils.fsync() requires a file descriptor as argument
but file object handle was being passed.

Change-Id: I316b58f6bc37de0945eff551e4e50565653664f5
Signed-off-by: Prashanth Pai <ppai@redhat.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Fix incorrect passing of file object to fsync()

swift.common.utils.fsync() requires a file descriptor as argument
but file object handle was being passed.

Change-Id: I316b58f6bc37de0945eff551e4e50565653664f5
Signed-off-by: Prashanth Pai <ppai@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Cleanup heat stacks 1 time per tenant

Heat stacks are tenant-based, it means that when manager is
returning list of stack for the whole tenant(not for user).
So when rally is cleaning up stacks it needs to delete it
only 1 time per tenant. Otherwise, it is very likely to get
"stack not found" errors in log.

Change-Id: Id8b0f967e2a1b35c8de1abdeee40fc060ce2a0d2
Closes-bug: #1450997

commit_message:
Router test enhancements

Add test to attach two routers to the same network
   -Create a network
   -Create a subnet
   -Create two port for the same network
   -Create two routers
   -Add router interface with the port_id for two routers by using respective port_ids
   -Verify the port device_id with that of router_id
   -Verify the port network id with that of created network

Change-Id: Id9de0edf687319b6e20804daee347b41d8b840a2

commit_message:
Do constraint validation for None value property

Should do constraint validation for None value property
when validate if the property has no dependency of any other
Init resource.

Change-Id: Ie22d01de517f25b1f160c84c8c94b8950e528399
Closes-Bug: #1444898

commit_message:
OVS-agent: Ignore IPv6 addresses for ARP spoofing prevention

The flow rules to match on ARP headers for spoofing prevention
fail to install when an IPv6 address is used. These should be
skipped since the ARP spoofing prevention doesn't apply to IPv6.

Co-authored-by: Kevin Benton <blak111@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1449363
Change-Id: I4bb3135e62378c5c96d1ac0b646336ac9a637bde

Add an option to generate template based on resource type

of template to generate.

Blueprint support-to-generate-hot-templates

History may have commits with non utf8 text in them. Rather than
forcing users to rebase, handle it gracefully.

Change-Id: I6f6302c815b02234e27ee31f7ce87eab101b40ea

commit_message:
Issue #1451976: handle commits with non-utf8 text

History may have commits with non utf8 text in them. Rather than
forcing users to rebase, handle it gracefully.

Change-Id: I6f6302c815b02234e27ee31f7ce87eab101b40ea
Closes-Bug: #1451976

keystone & openstacklib.

[{'created': '2015-03-13 15:35:04.000000000', 'message': 'Add contextlib2 lib to aid in py2/py3 compatability

The contextlib2 provides functionality of that exists
in the newer contextlib of python 3.2 and newer for
projects that wish to work seamlessly in 2.6/2.7 and
3.2 and newer they need this package to be able to
seamlessly use those python versions functionality.

This package exists on at least ubuntu 14.04 and
therefore is already being used/supported (and it
seems to have a fedora package as well).

TaskFlow would like to use it to provide use an
equivalent of the contextlib.ExitStack functionality
that exists in this library (and natively exists in
3.2 and newer). Oslo.db should also be able to take
advantage of the same functionality to replace some
test code (and likely other use-cases exist as well).

Change-Id: I328a29d0f095204dfbe175a9044e26ed653cb01d
'}]
commit_message:
Add contextlib2 lib to aid in py2/py3 compatability

The contextlib2 provides functionality of that exists
in the newer contextlib of python 3.2 and newer for
projects that wish to work seamlessly in 2.6/2.7 and
3.2 and newer they need this package to be able to
seamlessly use those python versions functionality.

This package exists on at least ubuntu 14.04 and
therefore is already being used/supported (and it
seems to have a fedora package as well).

TaskFlow would like to use it to provide use an
equivalent of the contextlib.ExitStack functionality
that exists in this library (and natively exists in
3.2 and newer). Oslo.db should also be able to take
advantage of the same functionality to replace some
test code (and likely other use-cases exist as well).

Change-Id: I328a29d0f095204dfbe175a9044e26ed653cb01d

commit_message:
Puppet: don't run beaker jobs on previous stable branches

Beaker tests have been introduced *after* Juno release, so it's a waste
of time and resource to run them now for stable/{havana,icehouse,juno}
since they will always fail.

Also keep non-voting for now when the job runs, until we stabilize the
tests.

Change-Id: Ib74e00229cff7177abce8dc68ae5ce6e0ae77d70

commit_message:
Add setup Docker script

This script will setup Docker environment for Kolla functional test.
This script will not affect the users exist Docker environment, only
added a new Docker binary to /usr/local/bin directory.

Change-Id: I9669461df198d9192e220b51cba1e034040d7ed3

tempest.

commit_message:
Add python-manilaclient to global requirements.

Upcoming project 'manila-ui' [1] is plugin for Horizon and it uses manilaclient
So, add it to requirements.

[1] Ib30c471d4cf6f17ec560266d3ab06427a9eb46be

Change-Id: I6cda1e9fdadd662101dbedf86342a4e2c4414ea1

commit_message:
Fix detach_sriov_ports to get context to be able to get image metadata

The previous implementation took the context using
get_admin_context() which return context with admin flag set,
but all the other attributes are None.
This is not sufficient to get image metadata,
it is need context with elevated permission.
The change here is to update API to pass the context to suspend so
it will be able to pass it to detach_sriov_ports.
Also update the snapshot method to pass context to detach_sriov_ports

(cherry picked from commit 6f002d26f28998c99d9922fdd49b0805c44ff22f)

Closes-Bug:#1406486
Change-Id: I4757a7646d7bee66db03c5d2410de7378c039d41

commit_message:
Fix mock return settings in test_full_uuids_skip_port_id_lookup

In the test_full_uuids_skip_port_id_lookup test in test_security_group.py,
there are a couple of problems with how a mock return value is being set
for a database query.

The first problem is that in this line:
    fmock = sess_mock.query.return_value.outerjoin.return_value.filter
there is a missing '.return_value' missing between 'sess_mock' and 'query'.

The second problem is that in this line:
    fmock.return_value.all.return_value = []
the 'all.return_value' should not be used.

For reference, the query for which this mock return value is being set
is in the get_sg_ids_grouped_by_port() method in ML2's db.py:
        query = session.query(models_v2.Port,
                              sg_db.SecurityGroupPortBinding.security_group_id)
        query = query.outerjoin(sg_db.SecurityGroupPortBinding,
                                models_v2.Port.id == sg_binding_port)
        query = query.filter(or_(*or_criteria))

This patch fixes the problems mentioned above so that the query above
returns an empty list for the test_full_uuids_skip_port_id_lookup test.

Change-Id: I2cec2c27fcdc82557c91205d202a6ac79987e92a
Closes-Bug: 1444009

commit_message:
Add python-tuskarclient to requirements

tripleo-common library will use tuskarclient to update tuskar plans
and roles (which are used for deploying Overcloud in TripleO).

Change-Id: I2dcbc0b9e6cc7d2ffa828d8e02a4580e5278331f

[{'created': '2015-04-14 15:05:51.000000000', 'message': 'Logging not using oslo.i18n guidelines (scheduler)

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses
the scheduler cinder directory.

There have been quite a few instances found where the
i18n guidelines are not being followed. I believe this
has helped lead to some of the confusion around how to
correctly do this. Other developers see this code and
assume it is an example of the correct usage.

This patch attempts to clean up most of those violations
in the existing codebase to hopefully help avoid some of
that confusion in reviews.

Some issues address:
* Correct log translation markers for different log levels
* Passing format values as arguments to call, not preformatting
* Not forcing translation via six.text_type and others

Guidelines can be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Hacking checks will not be able to identify all violations of
the guidelines, but it could be useful for catching obvious
one such as LOG.info("No markers!").

Change-Id: I0473ac402bc7b4a644c9b700df0fa2b88d82d705

commit_message:
Logging not using oslo.i18n guidelines (scheduler)

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses
the scheduler cinder directory.

There have been quite a few instances found where the
i18n guidelines are not being followed. I believe this
has helped lead to some of the confusion around how to
correctly do this. Other developers see this code and
assume it is an example of the correct usage.

This patch attempts to clean up most of those violations
in the existing codebase to hopefully help avoid some of
that confusion in reviews.

Some issues address:
* Correct log translation markers for different log levels
* Passing format values as arguments to call, not preformatting
* Not forcing translation via six.text_type and others

Guidelines can be found here:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Hacking checks will not be able to identify all violations of
the guidelines, but it could be useful for catching obvious
one such as LOG.info("No markers!").

Change-Id: I0473ac402bc7b4a644c9b700df0fa2b88d82d705
Partial-bug: 1433216

commit_message:
Heat topology display improvement

The current heat topology display is poor because a lot of resources
don't have any icons and are displayed as unknown resources.

openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/stacks/mappings.py file has
been modified to add the identification of the other resource types.

Icons were created for the others resources types, keeping the actual
style and put them in the openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/img/
folder.

Co-Authored-By: Antoine Abélard <abelard.antoine@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: David Lyle <david.lyle@intel.com>

Implements: blueprint heat-topology-display-improvement
Change-Id: I03f184e1561d27cda498c4d4d17be975069101bd

commit_message:
Return HTTP 400 for invalid sort_key

HTTP 500 (Internal Server Error) was being returned when a
request (eg node-list) specified an invalid sort_key. This is
because a DB exception was being raised that we weren't
handling.

We now raise an InvalidParameterValue exception with a message
that indicates that the sort key is invalid. The response is now
an HTTP 400 (Bad Request).

Change-Id: I237856ccb10e395bf2b42307804f607963b5dcbb
Closes-Bug: #1450552

So, the config-ref docs are auto-generated continually via automation scripts from the help text of options. And, IMO, this is A Good Thing.

In this case, the end user of this information is the cloud admin -- the person who creates flavors and tags compute nodes with capability extra specs. The target audience for this information is not really the Nova developer.

Now, if there are sections of the devref that need to inform the *developer* about some weird intricacies of the scheduler filters (and frankly, this is kind of one of them), then I think it's OK to have slightly duplicate information. commit_message:
Fix documentation for scheduling filters

ComputeCapabilitiesFilter will fail to pick a host if used
along with AggregateInstanceExtraSpecsFilter. This fix will at least
warn the users that they shouldn't use the two filters together.

Change-Id: I98b1eef6484bffc4305ff84e8badbde7992132ed

commit_message:
Add a method to skip cells syncs on instance.save

In order to move cells over fully to objects we need a way to save an
instance without it being synced to another cell.  Otherwise we end up
in a loop of syncs.  This adds a context manager on the instance object
to handle that case.

It uses it in instance_update_from_api which is a precursor to adding
object support to instance_update_at_top.

Change-Id: I7a3d96748bc2326ec0db679aaa5b9ce269df9e4c

So the logic you have implemented is good but we have to understand why libvirt complaints here. After investigate the code is seems that: 

in manager.py method _post_live_migration(...) we call self.driver.unfilter_instance() then we call self.driver.cleanup(), this method will also call the method unfilter_instance.

The problem can happens because of these two calls. What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:40:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@sahid, the driver.cleanup call is redundant but those aren't asynchronous operations so I don't think there is a problem there.  In a normal run, the _post_live_migration call in the manager to driver.unfilter_instance would undefine the network filter in the libvirt firewall driver.

The 2nd call via driver.cleanup should result in nw filter not found (I think?) which we just log as debug and move on.

The error is when the nw filter is still in use.  The comment in the code says that's due to the instance not being terminated properly, so maybe there is a race in some other destroy code in the libvirt driver, I'm not sure."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-29 17:43:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
libvirt: retry to undefine network filters during _post_live_migration

Sometimes post live migration fails because libvirt raises an error
saying the network filter is still in use.

Use the live_migration_retry_count config option (like in
pre-live-migrate) to retry the operation until it's successful or we
timeout.

Also adds some debug logging to _post_live_migration in the compute
manager before calling driver.unfilter_instance and driver.cleanup,
which calls unfilter_instance, so that when we hit this we can see
which path we're coming from.

Closes-Bug: #1438803

Change-Id: Idffbe2857fbb23fafab1591dea82f5d64edac4bc

If allow_duplicate_networks=False (it is by default) in neutron section
of Nova config, Neutron plugin raises NetworkDuplicated exception for
create instance operation when the same network is specified several
times. This exception is handled by v2 API, but not by v2.1. It leads to

commit_message:
Convert NetworkDuplicated to HTTPBadRequest for v2.1 API

If allow_duplicate_networks=False (it is by default) in neutron section
of Nova config, Neutron plugin raises NetworkDuplicated exception for
create instance operation when the same network is specified several
times. This exception is handled by v2 API, but not by v2.1. It leads to
500 internal server error as a result of the call.

This patch adds handling of the exception to return regular
HTTPBadRequest to a user.

Change-Id: Id7d3a3f9725252d999c96ac1ee8e0ff213848c6c

commit_message:
Initial support for taggable dependencies

Introduce a new --no-use-released-parent option to `build-docker-image`
that allows specifying whether the parent image uses the same tag as
the one that's currently build or the release tag.

Default is to use the release tag for parent image, however
`build-all-docker-images` script forces it to be the current tag.

Change to Dockerfile is coming next.

Change-Id: Ief11c9abb722c181ca85f38ee11800dbf4332a5f

commit_message:
Add 'Python API and CLI' section to spec template

It would be useful to have sections detailing the changes to the
Python API (and also the Trove CLI).  This would assist in making
sure the implementation includes all necessary pieces.

Also cleaned up some text (trying hard to keep the scope down
to very *minor* issues):
  - fixed comments/heading capitalization/whitespace
  - changed 'blueprint' to 'spec' where it made sense
  - enforced line lengths
  - added code for optional TOC and heading numbers

Change-Id: I82f728aaa389532586b4280b6eca37a3b3371d5e

commit_message:
Import xattr with sudo early on

xattr fails to import due to being unable to build cffi bindings unless
it is imported as root beforehand.

Change-Id: I6a9d64277974933ae9b7bbe2a40b8a0eb0fa8c6a
Closes-Bug: #1451992

commit_message:
Rally Test Framework Integration

* Integration of Rally framework in Cue project's and vagrant/devstack
* Added initial cluster create and delete scenario test
* Implemented initial scenario base class which inherits from rally's
  base.scenario and provides basic Cue CRUD interfacing
* To execute all Rally scenarios (currently one) in vagrant vm:
  1.  source admin user/tenant credentials for devstack environment
    > openrc admin admin
  2.  run script: run_rally_scenarios.sh (will run in verbose debug)
    > run_rally_scenarios.sh

Change-Id: I4e0015b69d9235d46fc785aa016c6d6f0e0caeb2

commit_message:
Import xattr with sudo early on

xattr fails to import due to being unable to build cffi bindings unless
it is imported as root beforehand.

Change-Id: I835e55bbafc7e0640987e6f3c8ee0c873f875ee0
Closes-Bug: #1451992

commit_message:
Remove adapter params from pypowervm calls

Recent changes in pypowervm removed now-redundant adapter parameters
from several methods.  Rebase on that change.

Change-Id: I88b5061150216359bcaab65a3c3587b622f61e14

commit_message:
Broker Unit and Functional tests

Unit tests for each of the cue-manage broker api functions. Functional
tests on the db/sqlalchemy/api.py broker functionality.  Broker
functionality tests on the broker object layer can be found here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176538/

Change-Id: Ibd0fd12b439e971fb123ea50970604c3123a78f9

commit_message:
Loosen validation on matching trusted dashboard

Instead of performing an exact matching for the validation if
origin is in trusted dashboard, loosen the check by comparing
the scheme and netloc of the URL instead.

Change-Id: I995214058c4071d9089a8f00b9b8002fd125fda0
Closes-Bug: #1440958

commit_message:
Enable taking the parent VIP range as a config param

As explained in the lined launchpad ticket, there is no way
to route to this VIP if it's always a link local IP. This patch
enables taking the parent VIP range as a config parameter.

Change-Id: I8ca2e4d58357d5dc96a48654f7bd5d7f6ffd8580
Partial-Bug: #1450882

This reverts commit 215cd551df8be066edafd2a1e16d0bd143ec214b

commit_message:
Revert "Bulk upload: treat user xattrs as object metadata"

This reverts commit 215cd551df8be066edafd2a1e16d0bd143ec214b

xattr doesn't appear to be working on some nodes in the gate
so this is killing quite a few jobs for other projects since
devstack is using glance to upload images for testing and
glance is configured with a swift backend.

Change-Id: I3cf747b4877041f42426f3e1c6a287b614f10689
Closes-Bug: #1451992

commit_message:
Validate languagepack defined in planfile during app create

When creating an app, users provide a planfile with a languagepack
id defined in it.

We want to validate that the LP exists during app creation itself.

Currently, the planfile gets stored in the DB and during app
deployment, if the LP does not exist, we log the error and
store the logs in the users swift container. The user now has to
look at the logs and then realizes that there is no LP with
the specified ID.

Change-Id: Ib7b673d3d5e88800010f3258071d296b7fc2d71f
Closes-bug: 1430469

commit_message:
Clean up usage.rst

Various changes to help usage.rst make more use of RST features,
particular inline code snippets.

The intent here is mostly to make the doc more readable by being more
clear about which values are exact filenames, exact network names, and
so on.

Change-Id: Ic7335379a3c036a1265cac7032042fa351d5606e

66% is obviously a trade-off. We assume that under 66% the translation become so incomplete to hurt users more than help.

I'm not a user of translations (and I suspect you aren't either). I actually am not personally convinced they are worth the effort. But the translations team thinks they are useful and actually produces them. So we asked their lead (Daisy) to decide on the number. They produce it, they should decide how much is necessary to "be useful" and how much is needed before they would consider we are "throwing away their work". They should decide the conditions under which they are comfortable shipping them.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-04-24 12:13:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add script to cleanup of translations

Add script for final translation sync on proposed branch:
* Import translation
* Remove partially translated files (less than 66 % as agreed on with
  Daisy and Thierry)
* Update source po files

Change-Id: If59fa00ebb9067ce509f64b5cebe28b502a1c49c

metadata with it by putting it in the request headers, prefixed with
"X-Object-Meta". However, if you're bulk-uploading objects, then you
have no way to assign any metadata.

The tar file format* allows for arbitrary UTF-8 key/value pairs to be
associated with each file in an archive (as well as with the archive
itself, but we don't care about that here). If a file has extended
attributes, then tar will store those as key/value pairs.

This commit makes bulk upload read those extended attributes, if
present, and convert those to Swift object metadata. Attributes
starting with "user.meta" are converted to object metadata, and
"user.mime_type"** is converted to Content-Type.

For example, if you have a file "setup.py":

    $ setfattr -n user.mime_type -v "application/python-setup" setup.py
    $ setfattr -n user.meta.lunch -v "burger and fries" setup.py
    $ setfattr -n user.meta.dinner -v "baked ziti" setup.py
    $ setfattr -n user.stuff -v "whee" setup.py

This will get translated to headers:

    Content-Type: application/python-setup
    X-Object-Meta-Lunch: burger and fries
    X-Object-Meta-Dinner: baked ziti

Swift will handle xattrs stored by both GNU and BSD tar***. Only
xattrs user.mime_type and user.meta.* are processed; others are
ignored.

This brings bulk upload much closer to feature-parity with non-bulk upload.

* The POSIX 1003.1-2001 (pax) format, at least. There are a few
  different, mutually-incompatible tar formats out there, because of
  course there are. This is the default format on GNU tar 1.27.1 or
  later.

** http://standards.freedesktop.org/shared-mime-info-spec/latest/ar01s02.html#idm140622087713936

*** Even with pax-format tarballs, different encoders store xattrs
    slightly differently; for example, GNU tar stores the xattr
    "user.rubberducky" as pax header "SCHILY.xattr.user.rubberducky",
    while BSD tar (which uses libarchive) stores it as
    "LIBARCHIVE.xattr.user.rubberducky". One might wonder if this is
    some programmer's attempt at job security.

commit_message:
Bulk upload: treat user xattrs as object metadata

Currently, if you PUT a single object, then you can also associate
metadata with it by putting it in the request headers, prefixed with
"X-Object-Meta". However, if you're bulk-uploading objects, then you
have no way to assign any metadata.

The tar file format* allows for arbitrary UTF-8 key/value pairs to be
associated with each file in an archive (as well as with the archive
itself, but we don't care about that here). If a file has extended
attributes, then tar will store those as key/value pairs.

This commit makes bulk upload read those extended attributes, if
present, and convert those to Swift object metadata. Attributes
starting with "user.meta" are converted to object metadata, and
"user.mime_type"** is converted to Content-Type.

For example, if you have a file "setup.py":

    $ setfattr -n user.mime_type -v "application/python-setup" setup.py
    $ setfattr -n user.meta.lunch -v "burger and fries" setup.py
    $ setfattr -n user.meta.dinner -v "baked ziti" setup.py
    $ setfattr -n user.stuff -v "whee" setup.py

This will get translated to headers:

    Content-Type: application/python-setup
    X-Object-Meta-Lunch: burger and fries
    X-Object-Meta-Dinner: baked ziti

Swift will handle xattrs stored by both GNU and BSD tar***. Only
xattrs user.mime_type and user.meta.* are processed; others are
ignored.

This brings bulk upload much closer to feature-parity with non-bulk upload.

* The POSIX 1003.1-2001 (pax) format, at least. There are a few
  different, mutually-incompatible tar formats out there, because of
  course there are. This is the default format on GNU tar 1.27.1 or
  later.

** http://standards.freedesktop.org/shared-mime-info-spec/latest/ar01s02.html#idm140622087713936

*** Even with pax-format tarballs, different encoders store xattrs
    slightly differently; for example, GNU tar stores the xattr
    "user.rubberducky" as pax header "SCHILY.xattr.user.rubberducky",
    while BSD tar (which uses libarchive) stores it as
    "LIBARCHIVE.xattr.user.rubberducky". One might wonder if this is
    some programmer's attempt at job security.

Change-Id: I5e3ce87d31054f5239e86d47c45adbde2bb93640

commit_message:
Rewrite ha_delete_vips test in failover_base

Now we delete VIPs 10 times and waiting its restoring

Add addtional method into FuelWebClient:
  get_devops_node_by_nailgun_node - get devops node by nailgun node
  get_devops_nodes_by_nailgun_nodes - the same as get_devops_node_by_nailgun_node
        but works for several nailgun nodes
  get_devops_node_by_nailgun_fqdn - return devops node by fqdn if exist
  get_devops_node_by_mac - get devops node by mac address
  get_nailgun_node_by_fqdn - get nailgun by it's fqdn
  get_nailgun_cluster_nodes_by_roles - return all nodes in cluster by roles
  get_pacemaker_resource_location - return devops nodes where resource is running

Changed method on FuelWebClient:
  ip_address_show - return str with ip or None instead of joinned stdout or ''
  find_devops_node_by_nailgun_fqdn - use get_nailgun_node_by_fqdn instead of
        internal function

Change-Id: I460e08cfca3421717d66f618a5f49176c639a55b
Closes-bug: #1412792
Closes-bug: #1422746
Closes-bug: #1441707

commit_message:
Set the neutron default workers
As stated in neutron's default conf file:
  # This feature is experimental until issues are addressed and testing
  # has been
  # enabled for various plugins for compatibility.

This change has been shown to be reliable in manual testing of the gate
jobs. These jobs had been seeing transient failures possibly leading
back to this value. The changes here have been set within the
`bootstrap-aio.sh` script such that gating is using a consistent
environment even if these options change their values in the
future.

Thanks to Evan Callicoat for doing the work to isolate the failures.

Change-Id: I98116eef94a7240addfdf449d116ec1c24260c59
Co-Authored-By: Evan Callicoat <evan.callicoat@rackspace.com>
Closes-Bug: #1425255
(cherry picked from commit caea2022232703f2f9f1501a16860baf1239d18b)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-30 17:35:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed YAQL tag leakage to YAML loader

Implicit yaml tag resolver being registered for YaqlYamlLoader (which is
user to load MuranoPL classes as YAML documents with embedded YAQL
statements) was being registered in the default YAML Dumper which is
used for any YAML serialization.

This was leading to inability to load more then one HOT-based package
per API service lifetime: the first package which was uploaded was
causing the leakage of YAQL statements into the global tag resolver.
This global resolver was used for all subsequent load attempts, so plain
yaml documents with Heat templates were attempted to be loaded as
MuranoPL classes.

This patch fixes this behavior by registering the implicit resolver
without helper method (which actually registers the resolvers at default
Dumper).

Change-Id: Icd3b6d354bcb105c2c25f842ede077d539e9c246
Closes-Bug: #1450547
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed YAQL tag leakage to YAML loader

Implicit yaml tag resolver being registered for YaqlYamlLoader (which is
user to load MuranoPL classes as YAML documents with embedded YAQL
statements) was being registered in the default YAML Dumper which is
used for any YAML serialization.

This was leading to inability to load more then one HOT-based package
per API service lifetime: the first package which was uploaded was
causing the leakage of YAQL statements into the global tag resolver.
This global resolver was used for all subsequent load attempts, so plain
yaml documents with Heat templates were attempted to be loaded as
MuranoPL classes.

This patch fixes this behavior by registering the implicit resolver
without helper method (which actually registers the resolvers at default
Dumper).

Change-Id: Icd3b6d354bcb105c2c25f842ede077d539e9c246
Closes-Bug: #1450547

commit_message:
Remove Logical Switch neutron:network_id External Id

When we create a logical switch we create it according to
the neutron network id:

lswitch name = 'neutron-' + network['id']

Thats why we dont really need to save the network id as external
id in the lswitch because its name reflect the id in a constant
way.
This patch remove network_id from lswitch external id's

Change-Id: I2abd9be3de6ef8e6857e23b30003f7f419907b1c

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I77e50f2f14345321d1b5319343c5872a92977936

commit_message:
Use retries for flavor-create

W/o this fix, keystone backend for tokens may
sporadically fail to find a token on each nova CLI command.
It may even fail if there would be a new token passed
as an argument for each CLI command.

For now, the solution is cannot be done at puppet side, but
only the workaround, which is to retry nova CLI commands

Related-bug: #1449584

Change-Id: I0f4895fe01c6811b89699677a46cbcecc6f04930
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Destroy container when container create failed

Currently, when create a container, we will create a container in
magnum database firstly, then we call docker client to create a
container (set container's uuid as hostname) on docker. But if docker
api failed, we won't destroy the corresponding container in magnum
database.

This patch call container.destroy() when container create failed.

Change-Id: I8f14319590b45b86dce184579ce9cdd8c88a8cf3
Closes-Bug: #1449872

commit_message:
Add ACL support on the API

Right now every authenticated user can perform administration actions on
CloudKitty's API. This patch uses oslo.context and oslo.policy to enable
a policy engine.

Enforcement of the policy will be added in another patchset.

Change-Id: Ia88a37b259f12aee00f65876686d12411297b8fb

commit_message:
Adding basic bandit config

This change adds a basic bandit config for sahara. It can be invoked by
running the tox environment for bandit; `$ tox -e bandit`. The tests are
based on the default bandit configuration with a few blacklist tests as
well. This is intended as a starting point for using bandit with sahara
and it should be revisited to improve the testing as more is learned
about the specific needs of the sahara code base.

* adding bandit.yaml configuration
* adding bandit to tox.ini
* adding a requirements file for bandit tox environment

Change-Id: I4b03f04dca80b146fdbae31a6b6011e78380d665

commit_message:
Hyper-V: checks for existent Notes in list_instance_notes

If there are VMs with Notes = None, the Hyper-V Driver cannot
start, as it tries to iterate over None, which results in an
exception.

This commit adds a check if the Notes exist, before iterating over
them.

Closes-Bug: #1438638

(cherry picked from commit 2c3da5462684c930436c9e91cb1e893e0936a331)

Change-Id: Icebdc03d7249fdf903b94b2f61f4891f5c9d6e50

commit_message:
Remove unused dependency on lockfile

We are trying to remove lockfile from the global requirements list in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/151224/. Murano is not yet in the list
of projects that sync requirements from the global list, but as an
official project it should be working on being added there. It will be
necessary to remove the dependency before that can happen.

Change-Id: I0793fbc3d94b995b79f8a184f5a2dd5017218a5c

commit_message:
Allow to re-define release/version parameters for rpmbuild

We can re-define release and version parameters while building
package(s) (for rpmbuild):
 * --define "release $RELEASE"
 * --define "version $VERSION"

Change-Id: Icb8dff8ec66f49ea0545cfbfebeae71aaa913c52
Related-blueprint:  package-fuel-components

commit_message:
Add basic functional tests for client library

We don't have a test coverage on neutronclient with HTTPClient.
CLI tests in our unit tests mock out the HTTP client and
We don't have a test combined with keystoneclient.
This leads to bugs in python bindings like bug 1431449.
Neutronclient has two backend HTTP client (HTTPClient and SessionClient)
so it is better to have functional tests for client library itself.

commit_message:
Fedora kernel install in ibp mode

Nailgun puts 'kernel_lt' flag in provisioning data and
if this flag is set, it is supposed that we need to install
kernel-lt package which is fedora kernel 3.10.
We assume both kernels are available in centos OS image:
2.6 and 3.10. We can just configure grub to boot with
one of those kernels. If flag 'kernel_lt' is NOT set, we
use 'vmlinuz-2.6' regexp for looking up for kernel file.
Otherwise we use default regexp 'vmlinuz' and sort available
kernels in backward direction, i.e. we use the newest available
kernel.

Co-Authored-By: Vladimir Kozhukalov <vkozhukalov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I1f7eee934440ce32d6e733c417e82f578b6d0c18
Partially-closes-bug: #1398643

commit_message:
Allow to re-define release/version parameters for rpmbuild

We can re-define release and version parameters while building
package(s) (for rpmbuild):
 * --define "release $RELEASE"
 * --define "version $VERSION"

Change-Id: I110910b4c620db56f7167957b368450f032b9f8d
Related-blueprint:  package-fuel-components

commit_message:
Add functional test for subnet create

This test adds a functional test to verify a subnet-create command
with the arg order used in the docs. python-neutronclient introduced
a regression which broke the usage of this order. This test will
prevent this from happening in the future.

Change-Id: If7e4211a4cbf33bc87a1304553ad3dc9c89346c4
Related-Bug: #1442771

commit_message:
fix checking in paging test

test test_tags_paging_with_differenet_filters checked that second page
will have another element than first page. but second page sometimes doesn't 
have it due to sorting.
just check that second page has more elements than first filter suites.

Change-Id: I930e3129e9e6e6c3797dd30b24aef6c9d8749a0d

commit_message:
Allow to re-define release/version parameters for rpmbuild

We can re-define release and version parameters while building
package(s) (for rpmbuild):
 * --define "release $RELEASE"
 * --define "version $VERSION"

Change-Id: I8884b79d9f5fbbaa4cc4f400a12fe2497c33ba82
Related-blueprint:  package-fuel-components

commit_message:
Implement --marker for event-list --nested-depth

Until the API supports recursive event listing, we can handle the
--marker option by locally slicing the list by the index of the
marker.

Change-Id: I680658c03f358f963fe4413f4adf7d8c224ee519

commit_message:
Change --force parameter into boolean

Change --force parameter into boolean, now user can use it as boolean,
without specifying True or False with it. It is still backward
compatible with --force True|False. This can be deprecated in future.

Closes-Bug: #1244453
Change-Id: Id245af1fa0db27912439a420c37aefca530894ba

commit_message:
Windows iSCSI: remove ensure_export

The ensure_export method is called by the manager when the service
is initialized, ensuring that in-use volumes are properly exported.

iSCSI targets exported by WinTarget persist after host reboot.
For this reason, the ensure_export method can simply pass, thus
simplifying the iSCSI target creation logic.

The patch set depending on this introduces CHAP credentials support.
If the iSCSI target is accidentaly deleted, the CHAP credentials
will change, so the volume won't be accessible anyway if the target
is recreated using ensure_export.

Change-Id: I5930e3f680dbba56a29ba45c1c43442498122546

commit_message:
Wait for the stack lock to be released

Sometimes, when trying to update a stack in a *_COMPLETE/FAILED status,
it can fail since the stack lock is not released yet. As a short-term
workaround, I've put in place an ugly hack that will simply retry the
update if the operation failed because of the stack lock. The downside of
this is that we can't now add functional tests which will test updates on
Stack Lock itself since we now simply just ignore the HTTPConflict Exception
on updates.

I couldn't think of another solution that doesn't include a giant refactoring
that will solve this problem.

PS: Convergence doesn't have the notion of a Stack-Lock, so that should
take care of this by default.

Partially-Closes Bug: #1450314

Change-Id: Ib1a9d5c425285ebcffcb9ff8a362a56fd8f3574a

If you get a chance, please take a look at: https://github.com/stackforge/openstack-chef-repo/blob/master/aio-neutron.rb with env: https://github.com/stackforge/openstack-chef-repo/blob/master/environments/vagrant-aio-neutron.json.   Or if multi-node is required, that is also started on in the testing repo, but does not work fully yet.'}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-04-27 23:56:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hello Mark.
Thanks for your review.

I thought that this patch work fully at vagrant_multi_neutron in my environment....
I will test again and revise it so this patch work well.

If you can , Please review again when I revised it.'}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-04-27 23:59:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 9970, 'date': '2015-04-28 15:00:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

When I was referring to the testing suite multi_neutron env, I may have been unclear.  Currently, both the aio_neutron and multi_neutron env in the testing suite do NOT fully work properly.  What I was suggesting is that we need to work on those a bit as well to make it a bit easier for neutrons patches to be tested.'}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-04-29 01:51:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-05-02 02:09:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-05-02 02:20:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

Hi all.
Thanks for your comments.

Mr Mark, I revised it so that both aio_neturon and multi_neutron work properly.
The reason why doesn't work is that I didn't enable external bridge(br-ex).So I Changed it.

Mr Neo,John,
I added comment to patch3.Please check it.
The summary is I think we don't need to support so much."}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-05-02 02:25:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Mr Neo, John.

Apparently , The past patch ( like patch set 3) don't reflect comment. 
So I write down it here.

----

John and Neo, You are right .
The ip which is moved go back according to setting file like /etc/network/interfaces or /etc/network/interfaces.d/<nic> .When "reboot" or "service network restart" after this code is used. 
But should we correspond to so much ?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-02 02:43:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-cookbook-openstack-network-chef-rake http://logs.openstack.org/81/177581/4/check/gate-cookbook-openstack-network-chef-rake/8cea349/ : SUCCESS in 32m 03s'}, {'account_id': 8172, 'date': '2015-05-05 05:26:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Yes. I think we should. Just think if someone has already moved ip address from interface to bridge by this recipe. And use this ip address as the remote access one(ssh). But for some reasons, the OS rebooted or network restart. Therefore, though it does has ip address, but its ip address can not be accessed any more(at least I can hit this issue in my environment).

I think it's very dangerous. Actually, we have do some more about ip movement. Do you mind we can implement it together?"}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:54:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Hi, Neo. 
I wrote my thought at launchpad (https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-chef/+bug/1350777). But just in case I also write here.

I have decided to cooperate your patch by reviewing it.
Therefore I abort this patch.

I'm looking forward to your patch.
Thanks."}, {'account_id': 14764, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:54:53.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add move ip from ext-bridge-iface to ext-bridge

I changed so that move ip from physical interface which is plugged to external
bridge to external bridge if physical interface have ip address.

Change-Id: I6f3ee743bb791393683e4be98291b9ed952e43e6
Closes-Bug: 1350777

commit_message:
Implement reload operation for Neutron DHCP agent

- added reload operation to Neutron DHCP agent resource
- enable artifacts cleanup on agent stop and start by default because
  fast restart is done using reload operation
- added dummy parameter to resource because it's needed for reload operation
  to work (see LP bug #1448160)

Related-bug: #1436414
Change-Id: I0dc9f9dd21ec938912a8b588d71da93397c73597

commit_message:
Allow to re-define release/version parameters for rpmbuild

We can re-define release and version parameters while building
package(s) (for rpmbuild):
 * --define "release $RELEASE"
 * --define "version $VERSION"

Change-Id: Id354ec9e7cf539c3f72ee61bc226da77a43d50cf
Related-blueprint:  package-fuel-components

commit_message:
Notify a consumer that all dependenices injected

In the current DI implementation a provider is registered when it is
constructed, without providing any prior information. Technically we
can't guarantee that a dependency will be injected before a consumer
object construction, because the provider object could be instantiated
later on. Moreover this problem is not applicable just to __init__
method, the consumer object is inconsistent state for some time and any
methods which rely on injected attribute will fail during this period.

This fix adds a callback method _dependencies_injected which a consumer
may implement. This method will be invoked when all required
dependencies has been injected.

Change-Id: I7e04f04dadd99da73eca5a446b4958b0f0d0feb9
Closes-Bug: #1180136

commit_message:
Backup all container images together

With common fat base image for docker containers,
it is much faster to back up all of them together.
Additionally, this is now possible since Docker
upgrade beyond 1.2.

Change-Id: Icbf3497d58b6f880eb945a952cb23dcdca98e9b1
Related-Bug: #1336911

commit_message:
Update packages on master node before bootstrap

In order to tests manifests and scripts which are
used during master node deployment we should upload
their packages and install them (update installed)
before starting puppet apply and building docker
containers.

Related: blueprint package-fuel-components

Change-Id: I540173cd1324c9e6caf1a173d7a307b5f9de4470

commit_message:
Allow to re-define release/version parameters for rpmbuild

We can re-define release and version parameters while building
package(s) (for rpmbuild):
 * --define "release $RELEASE"
 * --define "version $VERSION"

Change-Id: If8765c069a51a57086a1fb363f4d858c78386fbe
Related-blueprint:  package-fuel-components

We're not going to start accepting a separate patch for each cinder driver because no one was testing this in their ci env. There is a specific way to exclude this test which requires no input from tempest. Just skip the test in your ci's job configuration. It's a simple regex exclude to add to your testr (or whatever exclude mechanism your test runner uses) and it requires no input from any project teams to add it in your ci env.

The ceph case was slightly different. An explicit skip was added because the job was going to be made voting everywhere except for one issue which was clearly in an OpenStack project and a fix was already proposed for it. Honestly, it probably shouldn't have been accepted for ceph either, and the test runner exclude should have been used instead. But, since the fix for that already landed the inline skip will be removed, so we don't have a chance to switch it to the proper approach."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-04-13 17:20:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Matthew,
  It seems ianw in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/173408/11
is proposing to skip the test in tempest itself (as done
in this patch) with the below reasoning (quoting Ian...):

"However, I'd like to see further discussion on that. It seems very unreasonable that tempest will not accept work-arounds for drivers. devstack-gate is not the only way that tempest gets run, so information such as known incompatibilities like this should be kept within tempest itself not stuck in a completely separate job. if someone went to setup a third-party CI with glusterfs for whatever reason, they would have to go and rediscover this whole issue when a simple @skip in tempest would make it completely explicit."'}]

commit_message:
Skip test_volume_boot_pattern for GlusterFS until bug 1441050 is fixed

From the past couple of weeks the job
"check-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs-nv" is failing because of two
reasons:
1. Empty provider location of 'volume from snapshot'
2. Nova/Libvirt doesn't support delete snapshot when vm is off

Look at Bug 1441050 for more details.
Patch [1] partially closes Bug 1441050.

The cinder glusterfs CI job started failing recently when
test_volume_boot_pattern was enabled in tempest, before which
the CI job was running successfully.

Hence, I am proposing this patch to skip test_volume_boot_pattern
for GlusterFS backend, until Nova/Libvirt issue is fixed.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/171482

Related-Bug: #1441050
Change-Id: Idb7c3ff70ac066ba55c57df0f6cb07b100a7413b

commit_message:
Enhance configure_for_func_testing.sh for *aaS use

Modify the script so that it can be used by the *aaS functional tests.
This is done by allowing callers, namely other *aaS repos, to override
information, like the project name and virtual environment used (for
example, VPNaaS has two functional jobs with different virtual env).

Change-Id: I450273036e938a4acc9a7bc1dc193a9c207b2d58
Closes-Bug: #1446807

commit_message:
Set mtu for internal networks according to segmentation type

Currently MTU for cloud networks is always set to 1500, which is not correct
for GRE segmentation and causes performance degradation. MTU value should also
depend on MTU settings of physical interfaces.
The only way to change MTU for Neutron private network is to use an additional
dnsmasq configuration file.

Change-Id: I1fa979639c187e6f6d416100efc2a6548e141c50
Closes-bug: #1411732

(3 comments)

I see this is being proposed as a new driver, but iPXE is a boot mechanism rather than a deploy mechanism.  We already have a planned item to separate boot interface from deploy interface. 
Can't we separate out iPXE into a boot interface rather.

So in the end, we will have 3 boot mechanisms (PXE, iPXE, VirtualMedia) and 2 deploy mechanisms (DIB iSCSI, IPA) - so a total of 6 deploy mechanisms."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-10-27 17:21:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Thanks for the review guys

@Ramakrishnan, about the boot interface, I took a look at it and while it seems logical to split the deploy interface into two (boot and deploy) it's not as straight forward as I thought. The PXE used for the iSCSI and the PXE for the agent for example are very different. I might be wrong but I see the boot interface depending on the deploy method so there's a dependency there. For e.g if we are going to deploy a OS with UEFI enabled, we have to boot it in UEFI mode[1], we need to know what the deployment is about in order to boot it accordingly. The PXE templates as well, they contain information about the deploy, for e.g ipa-api-url for the agent or iscsi_target_iqn for the iSCSI. So in the end the boot interface is dependent of the deploy method, so maybe the split is not actually beneficial.

[1] Otherwise the installer won't have access to things like `efibootmgr` to configure the UEFI boot menu and the installation is going to fail."}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2014-10-28 14:15:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2014-10-28 14:16:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-28 14:25:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
New stateless iPXE driver

Add a new iPXE driver that will use advanced features of iPXE by scripting
the boot process to generate the PXE configuration on-the-fly and boot
images from a Swift temp URLs, so that we not cache anything in the
local conductor disk.

This is the stage 1 of proposing a spec for Liberty, in this stage we
should determine whether the idea is in the scope and in alignment with
project direction.

Change-Id: I6d74c02ef2de0693ec91029891fd67a7be849677

commit_message:
Shifting _generate_random_name() call to utils

Rather than calling _generate_random_name() multiple times in scenarios.
Better to call it once inside utils.
Affected method _create_image() of glance secnario.
Closes- Bug: 1412014

Co-Authored-By: Roman Vasilets <rvasilets@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Shaifali Agrawal <agrawalshaifali09@gmail.com>

Change-Id: If0b6f358f4087d9c35d4af9cd4e22ea601c757d2

commit_message:
Added support for pluggable tenant fetcher

CloudKitty doesn't rely on Keystone at all anymore.
Moved Keystone related code in a new driver so that tenant list fetching
can be pluggable.
Only keystone fetcher is implemented at the moment.

Change-Id: Ib9de445b93f16696e6b9d205a6101a902349b76e

(2 comments)

> [WIP] Try running a single test module with python34

Do you prefer that I write a single huge patch instead of multiple smaller patchess?

I wrote a tool to apply a single change to the whole Nova code base at once because I consider that such generated patch is easier to review. Since it was generated, it's also easier to rebase it: in case of conflict, rerun the tool instead of manually fixing each conflict.

I sent 8 patches generated by my tool sixer.py. When these patches will be merged, it will become interesting to start to write a whitelist of unit tests which pass and add a check job for them.

My patches:
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:openstack/nova+branch:master+topic:bp/nova-python3,n,z"}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-05-05 10:29:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Victor,

I was trying to see for myself what it would take to get to the point of - "whitelist of unit tests which pass and add a check job for them". I am going to abandon this review/experiment.

As feedback,
1. I'd like to see a patch series so others can contribute
2. I'd like to see us get quickly (shortest length of patch series) that will get us to the white list of unit tests and the check job.

my 2 cents, so you are not bound to it of course :)

thanks,
dims'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-05-05 10:29:56.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Remove unneeded MANIFEST.in

pbr includes the contents of git by default. The graft lines here will
at best cause unversioned things to be included in tarballs, and the
explicit includes only include things in git.

Tested by building an sdist before and after and checking - no
difference in contents.

commit_message:
Delete redundant resource.id checking

Delete redundant resource.id checking for floatingip resources,
since the resource.id won't be None when enter handle_*().

Change-Id: I73e5ef8fbaa7fb47ef9ae222a3c8191d708e8b43

Add multi vm scenario test

Tests read/write action across two launched vms. Adapt basic_ops
test to support multiple vm instances.

Change-Id: I3e14fab3c70f3c109d22f172ba2ad49db5914d33
Partially-implements: blueprint scenario-tests

[root@fuel remote]# ll /var/log/remote/
lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   17 Jan  4 07:11 10.20.7.3 -> node-1.domain.tld
drwxr-xr-x 5 root root 4096 Apr 22 07:20 node-1.domain.tld'}, {'account_id': 11082, 'date': '2015-04-23 09:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

IMHO we should also remove logs when we remove nodes from env. Because then we will avoid case from bug: https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1428150 . And also we avoid cases when you will have logs from 2 envs in one node'}, {'account_id': 8053, 'date': '2015-04-23 09:44:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Guys, I would vote against removing logs together with removing node from environment. Let's assume such case: we may remove node in 'error' state from working environment to avoid some data corruption or "bad influence" on cluster, and we should be able to investigate logs from that node after removing. Configured logrotate & compression mechanism is usually a proper solution in such cases, not deletion.'}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-04-23 09:54:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Folks, we should simply remove logs when node is removed from the environment. There is absolutely no point in keeping them, as you can't know where the node will be added. Resulting logs will be completely confusing during debug sessions. Logrotate is a solution for log rotation, not complex logic regarding cleaning up anything. Let's not make our /var/log situation more difficult than it is now."}, {'account_id': 11082, 'date': '2015-04-23 10:31:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

You can remove logs when you redeploy node, but still we need them to be removed when you remove and next redeploy this node. In other case you can have logs from 2 envs for one node if you remove node from env1 and add node to different env2.'}, {'account_id': 15454, 'date': '2015-04-23 13:45:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Delete logs on master after node or env deletion

Added delete_node_logs function to utils which is called in
NailgunReciever.remove_nodes_resp after node deletion
(just before removing it from database).

Closes-Bug: #1428825
Change-Id: I828e515c7f5d1e39373d351809e583cd732836c1

commit_message:
Add l23network puppet call to fuelmenu

It is now a requisite class for calling
l23network::l3::ifconfig for a given
interface, so now it should be included
in the puppet call.

Change-Id: Iee15a6bd9ce895cca931055e45cd3a42d0594cc7
Related-Bug: #1426573

commit_message:
Describe the bug reporting process in more detail

For vulnerability reporters who are newcomers to online bug tracking
systems, a little additional instruction on filing security bugs can
help reduce mistakes and requests for assistance with the process.

Change-Id: I2d40b2aec377c63b0f50796abd406fa21265071f

commit_message:
Fix commands transfer in OpsGuide

The commands present in How to backport
Galera Pacemaker OCF script are split
incorrectly and, thus, cannot be used with
simply copying them from the guide and pasting
right into the terminal.

This commit fixes the problem.

Change-Id: Ia000bade42c0646a870b1e7f484067f1a1d1c82a
Closes-Bug: 1443919

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch

    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Commit transactions after an exception in a task

Tasks are now executed in mules so when an exception
happens during an execution of one, task status is updated
but not commited to the database because mules start separate
transactions.

This patch adds a commit clause to the error handler in tasks.

Closes-bug: #1436821
Closes-bug: #1446651
Change-Id: I6c17d1cd88321940f2e23379965675e6b185ab1e

[{'created': '2015-04-30 14:27:28.000000000', 'message': '[IBP] Fix ValueError while parsing: mdadm --detail

Backport from 6.1

fuel-agent doesn't expect header from 'mdadm --detail' output where
'State' is not present.

fuel-agent should expect 2 types of headers:
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice State\n" (already supported)
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice\n" - addressed by this patch.

This patch is required to let fuel-agent consume both types of headers.

Additionally fuel-agent will start to log 'mdadm --detail' output to ease
troubleshooting.

Change-Id: Ie20db2c14bdc5669566a140a34d63d28c6115d11
Closes-Bug: #1446186
(cherry picked from commit 5283060fdef4e3125cefe1e4f2b2c24cc1698a7c)
'}]
commit_message:
[IBP] Fix ValueError while parsing: mdadm --detail

Backport from 6.1

fuel-agent doesn't expect header from 'mdadm --detail' output where
'State' is not present.

fuel-agent should expect 2 types of headers:
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice State\n" (already supported)
" Number Major Minor RaidDevice\n" - addressed by this patch.

This patch is required to let fuel-agent consume both types of headers.

Additionally fuel-agent will start to log 'mdadm --detail' output to ease
troubleshooting.

Change-Id: Ie20db2c14bdc5669566a140a34d63d28c6115d11
Closes-Bug: #1446186
(cherry picked from commit 5283060fdef4e3125cefe1e4f2b2c24cc1698a7c)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-30 20:37:51.000000000', 'message': "chmod /etc/neutron to 755 instead of 750

Packaging sets /etc/neutron to 755 [1] while Puppet sets it to 750, that
brings Puppet run not idempotent (by the way, we try to avoid to
Puppetize packaging things, like permissions, users, groups,
directories, files).

Set it to 755 to be consistent with packaging and keep Puppet
idempotent.

[1] Second run of Puppet:
/Stage[main]/Neutron/File[/etc/neutron]/mode: mode changed '0755' to
'0750'

Change-Id: I661b0ea94e151a47ab71355058f7ac971915c116
"}, {'created': '2015-05-04 14:09:53.000000000', 'message': "Don't manage chmod for /etc/neutron and neutron.conf

Debian/Ubuntu & Fedora packaging use different modes that mean Puppet will
override the mode and break idempotency between runs.

This patch aims to drop the modes for /etc/neutron and neutron.conf to
ensure idempotency between runs.

[1] Second run of Puppet on Ubuntu:
/Stage[main]/Neutron/File[/etc/neutron]/mode: mode changed '0755' to

Change-Id: I661b0ea94e151a47ab71355058f7ac971915c116
"}]
commit_message:
Don't manage chmod for /etc/neutron and neutron.conf

Debian/Ubuntu & Fedora packaging use different modes that mean Puppet will
override the mode and break idempotency between runs.

This patch aims to drop the modes for /etc/neutron and neutron.conf to
ensure idempotency between runs.

[1] Second run of Puppet on Ubuntu:
/Stage[main]/Neutron/File[/etc/neutron]/mode: mode changed '0755' to
'0750'

Change-Id: I661b0ea94e151a47ab71355058f7ac971915c116

commit_message:
Enable a check job for stackforge/dragonflow

Enable a simple test for stackforge/dragonflow, verify
that we can bring devstack up with dragonflow

Currently this is non-voting

Change-Id: I840a042acc009cc48eb41f8df04b80f59c4617b0

commit_message:
Clarify Identity logging

It wasn't obvious that log_config is a config option.

etc/logging.conf.sample is a file and not a directory.

Change-Id: Ia0f46a0101e4a8d91ae4ec93314899bccd76c94a

commit_message:
Remove auth_token from logging

auth_token configuration doesn't have anything to do with logging,
so remove the auth_token configuration docs from the logging
section.

Change-Id: Ieb484ace858b936fa8a612d6e474d160e610a846

commit_message:
Amendments to the introduction of policy.json

This is an amendment of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/166853/,
after additional information became available.
Specifically, information about the is_admin flag and a note on
tweaking policy.json are added, and some points reworded for
clarity.

While there is still room for improvement, the bug, previously
declared as partially fixed, can be closed now.

Change-Id: Ifd01bc4e367f65d6ce45c54a005bafb660535260
Closes-Bug: #1311067

commit_message:
Further improvements for openstack-auto-commands

* new command for trove-manage
* automatically identify deprecated subcommands
* move client definitions into a YAML resource file
* support of the complete subcommand
* add new clients: barbican, designate, manila, magnetodb,
  manila, mistral, tuskar

Clients to be added in the future:

  * congress (module for python-openstackclient)
  * magnum (no released version)
  * murano (missing --version parameter)
  * zaqar (module for python-openstackclient)

Change-Id: I5ccb5af887749ec22a9d980e3b031de6a247041e

commit_message:
Provide and use a options collapsing function

Instead of having each driver index the last value of
each option, when all current drivers do not actually care
about any of the other indexes we can just use and provide
a option collapsing function that we by default apply to
all the existing drivers options (to avoid needing to index
by -1).

This avoids a confusion point for new folks, and one that
does not currently really provide any value (no driver in
tree besides one option in the redis driver uses/consumes
or understands multiple options in the first place).

Change-Id: Ia2898d84fd0e54871b829f4a95786a33accc20b8

commit_message:
Allow providing the deprecation category

Instead of always using 'DeprecationWarning' it can be useful
to allow for 'PendingDeprecationWarning' to be used instead (or
other category); so enable this category passing and usage
by providing yet another keyword argument (that when not provided
defaults to 'DeprecationWarning').

Change-Id: I6719afd44bae99da31d09d429f8aa9402af194fc

commit_message:
Add RST infrastructure for HA Guide

This adds the basic infrastructure for building and checking the HA
guide using RST.

The guide is not published to draft yet, this should be done once
there's real content.

Partially implements bp improve-ha-guide
Co-Authored-By: Nick Chase <nchase@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
indexer: use binary UUIDType

There's no good reason except bug #1368297 to use textual representation
of UUID. Let's switch to binary as soon as oslo.db is fixed.

Change-Id: Iabc7b2d4aa886b2a4e80dd1cb4e4033b55a07a69

subject: sqlalchemy: use RDBMS check constraint where available

commit_message:
sqlalchemy: use RDBMS check constraint where available

We replace our Python check by a check in the DB for != MySQL.

This requires change I7e36ef4385b227d1e62e18277d470047a369a238 in
oslo.db to be released.

Change-Id: I6027ac0159dddc3e8bf50a6a86e1d50f325e9d6d

commit_message:
Add django-openstack-auth-kerberos project

The django-openstack-auth-kerberos package provides additional modules
and handles kerberos related dependencies for kerberos authentication to
horizon.

Depends-On: Id9bd9d18777c1620ef7009d033f9b6ead051685d
Change-Id: Ied438ddc420a875361c83b7eafa7b169eb19bfd1

Add install_test_deps script

This is useful for users and for CI so we do not have to chase infra for
changes when dependency issues arise.

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

commit_message:
Fixed container user create issue

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

Change-Id: I81d0e8b0d8e9e431cd8eebd43ceaffab7e61b207
Closes-Bug: 1437054

Fix unnecessary capitalization in security-guide

Corrected capitalization of the phrase "port mirroring" under the
QoS subsection in section_networking-services.xml

Co-Authored-By: Shellee Aragon <shellee.arnold@hp.com>
Change-Id: Id07fb18f6fa7e644cbc129a5769fe4d46701dee8

commit_message:
Add ScalingInPolicy and ScalingOutPolicy

These two simple scaling policies are just used to support some
existed use cases of autoscaling where user may want to define
webhook trigger condition without Senlin's help. In most cases,
users are recommonded to use ScalingPolicyComplex to provide
autoscaling support of a cluster.

Implements: blueprint scaling-policy-simple
Change-Id: I2ce01b68e055c94cebac230fce25adb0d04f14fa

commit_message:
Fixes issues with tempest

The tempest role has an entry within the defaults of the role and
it could cause confusion when dealing with tempest as the main
package version is being specified in
`vars/repo_packages/openstack_services.yml`. Being that these
variables are no longer used they have been removed.

Implements blueprint: master-kilofication

Change-Id: I197afac1ce50d9bad778dda5cc4a23a0821fceeb

(2 comments)

Detecting which modules are being copied come from oslo.config options. Those can be passed on the command line, separately from the config file, and we support only copying some of the files at any given time as well as not using the configuration file at all. Re-parsing the config file to figure out the list does not accurately reflect what the instructions were.

The way the config file is actually parsed allows multiple values for the "modules" option on the same line, separated by a comma, so we can't assume that the file will be formatted with one on a line or that the lines or module names will be in order. Barbican, melange, and a couple of the client libraries have their modules listed this way.

I'm not sure how smart we want to make this program, so I don't know if we want to worry about addressing any of these issues. I would rather we spend time on graduations and improving libraries than this particular tool.'}, {'account_id': 9796, 'date': '2014-10-20 02:23:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

commit_message:
Add module integrity check in update.py

OpenStack projects use file openstack-common.conf to track modules copied
from oslo-incubator, developers need update this file before syncing code
if need. There is inconsistent issue, like copied modules are not tracked
in file openstack-common.conf or removed modules still exist in the
file. This commit check consistency between modules in openstack-common.conf
and oslo-incubator modules in directory 'openstack/common'.

There is no usage change and only output warning and info message. This is
an usage example: http://paste.openstack.org/show/122027/

Closes-Bug: #1295582

Change-Id: I68c0108304be8a315bcefe939c22019caab9bc98

commit_message:
libvirt: check qemu version for NUMA & hugepage support

In commit 945ab28 the libvirt driver was modified to validate the
libvirt version before enabling NUMA and hugepage support.

While good, it's not sufficient.  We also need to check the qemu
version since NUMA hugepage support wasn't added until version 2.1.
(See http://wiki.qemu.org/ChangeLog/2.1#x86, specifically the
memory-backend-* objects.)

We know that qemu on the s390x doesn't support NUMA or hugepages.
Support for ppc64 is possible but not yet determined...we can
update the supported list once we find out for sure.

Change-Id: Ib31c4f806e30a8b33669d5a15bd1578050c7e352
Closes-Bug: #1422775

This function deletes all servers in the current tenant, which is
almost certainly The Wrong Thing. It's also poorly written: it deletes

commit_message:
Remove _delete_all_servers() nova utils function

This function deletes all servers in the current tenant, which is
almost certainly The Wrong Thing. It's also poorly written: it deletes
the servers sequentially, not in parallel; and it creates multiple
timers for the same action. A subsequent commit will add support for
deleting multiple specific servers at once.

Change-Id: Ib381fcc93d77bf417ce7d90c90261ca0209c1bbb

[{'created': '2015-04-28 00:05:05.000000000', 'message': 'Actually set a sane PATH for inside chroot

In I084aff7e449f5de811a6169ec90e352ada7da439 we attemped to address a
bug for systems which dont have a path that works well for inside a
chroot. Turns out there were multiple issues:
 * The PATH we were setting was after we attempted to call sh.
 * PATH was being set in a sibling process to the command being run.
 * PATH was not being exported so it was not effecting child processes.

Using env to set a sane path before we attempt to run our commands
addresses these issues.

Change-Id: I4285f8048465ee5c2490116447d32033007bd185
'}]
commit_message:
Actually set a sane PATH for inside chroot

In I084aff7e449f5de811a6169ec90e352ada7da439 we attemped to address a
bug for systems which dont have a path that works well for inside a
chroot. Turns out there were multiple issues:
 * The PATH we were setting was after we attempted to call sh.
 * PATH was being set in a sibling process to the command being run.
 * PATH was not being exported so it was not effecting child processes.

Using env to set a sane path before we attempt to run our commands
addresses these issues.

Change-Id: I4285f8048465ee5c2490116447d32033007bd185

commit_message:
VMware: Enable vCenter certificate verification

Currently vCenter certificate is not verified during connection
establishment. This patch adds a config option to specify a CA
bundle file to verify vCenter server certificate.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ida730db66b154a4d445f7a91bccb9ca5b5a26f5e
Closes-Bug: #1276207

commit_message:
Option name missing from ConfigFileValueError

It's sometimes hard to find the option with a bad value.  In a
couple ConfigFileValueError cases, the option is not included in
the log message.

Change-Id: Ib373f5184b7339ebd59a6d7eb53f3b02a5d59f4f
Closes-Bug: #1451479

Thank you for this, I understand the intent of the clean up. I would point out line #1849 of manager.py where "i_info" is used. If the goal is to be more consistent, then maybe switching instance_info to i_info would be better. shortening the var would also allow for the "if" to be a single line vs the wrapped line it is now..'}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-04-30 03:33:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

thanks for the suggestion Chris, will address it in the coming patch set :)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-30 13:14:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

@Zhenguo, thanks for updating the commit message. But I still don't see the advantage of making this change, to what had been there before. If there's no advantage, then I don't see the reason for making this change.

@Chris, I actually prefer 'instance_info' to 'i_info' :)"}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-04-30 14:29:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Ruby, this is just a code clean up, the original looks strange that we use a short alias for some but others don't. this small change makes code clean and don't bring in any hurt, could you please consider accepting it :)"}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-30 15:10:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Zhenguo, what do you mean by "use a short alias for some but other's don't"? What is the 'short alias' you are referring to, and where is it being used and where is it not being used?

I have no problems with the code change itself. I just don't see the reason for making the change because I also don't have a problem with the existing code. There is more than one way to code...?'}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-04-30 23:08:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Ruby I mean we used node.instance_info 3 times in the same function at L707,L709,and  L710.  but  we set instance_info = node.instance_info  at L708  then we can directly use instance_info instead of  node.instance_info at L709-710, but at L707 we have to use node.instance_info.'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-30 23:55:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Zhenguo. Thanks for explaining. I don't really see a problem with the way the code is now. If the 'if glance_utils.is_glance_image(node.instance_info.get('image_source')) proves to be false, then there would have been no reason to alias it at all.

Honestly, if I were to review the code, I'd accept either version. Whoever submitted the code wrote it that way; I just don't see that it is 'wrong' enough that it warrants changing how they wrote it.

Like I said, there is nothing wrong with your change. But I haven't seen any good justification for changing it. It isn't fixing anything that is wrong and I don't feel like it is improving anything. So I don't think it should be merged. But that is my opinion; others may think differently."}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2015-05-01 00:00:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Generally if we want to enforce a certain code style, we add a hacking rule while fixing the code to pass the new rule.

I appreciate the effort and concern, but I think that without an accompanying rule to enforce the style change, it'll simply change back over time. 

I don't care if this particular patch merges or not, but overall I think there are likely better places you could fix things up in the future :)"}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2015-05-01 12:22:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I agree with about everything Ruby and Jay have stated.

I personally believe the code looks moderately cleaner and is somewhat easier to follow with the change, however everyone's brains will process information slightly differently.

For what its worth, consider line 721 and the conditional not being met."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2015-05-01 12:24:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

And ignore my comment re: line 721.  Everyone's brains process data differently.  Clearly mine needs coffee."}, {'account_id': 13295, 'date': '2015-05-04 21:52:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I actually prefer the old version a bit just because the instance_info variable won't be created unnecessarily if the boolean test fails. I think it was already pretty legible if a little verbose.

Also agree with Jay's comment about enforcing this in the hacking file if we want this.

It looks like there are other small changes to this section of the code that people have suggested, so I might +1 it if the refactoring encompasses a little more than a contentious line."}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-05-05 01:01:26.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
A small code rearrange

Currently we have a instance_info alias for node.instance_info
but not for all, so move the alias before we use it to keep
code clean and consistent.

Change-Id: Id2ce5c4daa8514800ed2351f8dad122310081d61
