BTW, random thought - should we be creating indexes for this table?'}, {'account_id': 11424, 'date': '2015-03-06 13:07:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

The primary keys will be indexed by default. Hence our get operations should be fast.
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1071180/is-the-primary-key-automatically-indexed-in-mysql


mysql> show index from sync_point;
+------------+------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+-----------+-------------+----------+--------+------+------------+---------+---------------+
| Table      | Non_unique | Key_name    | Seq_in_index | Column_name  | Collation | Cardinality | Sub_part | Packed | Null | Index_type | Comment | Index_comment |
+------------+------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+-----------+-------------+----------+--------+------+------------+---------+---------------+
| sync_point |          0 | PRIMARY     |            1 | resource_id  | A         |           0 |     NULL | NULL   |      | BTREE      |         |               |
| sync_point |          0 | PRIMARY     |            2 | traversal_id | A         |           0 |     NULL | NULL   |      | BTREE      |         |               |
| sync_point |          0 | PRIMARY     |            3 | is_update    | A         |           0 |     NULL | NULL   |      | BTREE      |         |               |
| sync_point |          1 | fk_stack_id |            1 | stack_id     | A         |           0 |     NULL | NULL   |      | BTREE      |         |               |
+------------+------------+-------------+--------------+--------------+-----------+-------------+----------+--------+------+------------+---------+---------------+
4 rows in set (0.00 sec)


For update operations also it should be relatively fast since only atomic_key is not indexed.
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5174278/mysql-and-mssql-using-both-indexed-and-non-indexed-columns-in-where-clause'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-03-07 00:31:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Agreed on those two, and that just leaves the case where we clean up by deleting all entries with a particular stack_id, but it looks like from the output you pasted that there is an index on that column already.'}, {'account_id': 11424, 'date': '2015-03-07 02:16:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yes, in mysql the foreign key constraint is also indexed.

But not in other DB's http://stackoverflow.com/questions/970562/postgres-and-indexes-on-foreign-keys-and-primary-keys
 
And since delete operation is done only on each update, I think it should be fine if we dont index this column.

(relative to get/update operations, delete operations performed is very less, i.e, only once per update)"}, {'account_id': 11424, 'date': '2015-03-08 08:50:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Convergence prepare traversal

Generates the graph for traversal in convergence.

* Updates current traversal for the stack
* Deletes any sync_point entries of previous traversal
* Generates the graph for traversal based on
  - resources loaded from db for the stack
  - resources that exist in present template
* Stores resource.current_template_id and resource.requires
* Stores the edges of graph in stack.current_deps
* Creates sync_points for each node in graph
* Creates sync_point for stack.

blueprint convergence-prepare-traversal

Change-Id: I507e67b39c820ed46d3b269fc76d6cf18d0ef2d7

commit_message:
Adopt config generator

oslo.config.generator has been removed from olso-incubator so
we need to adopt it in order to generated up-to-date config
files.
Changes introduced:
- Move config/generator.py from openstack.common to ironic.common
- Update config generator to use new style list_opts discovery
- Split _print_opt function to reduce complexity and pass pep8 tests

Change-Id: I397504bf0604a86082f26e46952720117611f3a8

This looks very interesting.  I am probably going to do a couple of passes over the code.  The first pass will be mainly on the Go code itself, and then work on what the Go code is doing.'}, {'account_id': 16177, 'date': '2015-05-01 04:29:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(24 comments)

Lots of little nits.

Some overall comments

Every public symbol needs a comment in the style

// X does Y. 
// X also has the side effect of fooing Z.
// If X succeeds it will return a Q.
func X(...) ... {   }

Errors are not handled well throughout, far to many errors are being assigned to the _ variable and the other returned arguments assumed to be valid. The short version is, unless you check the error, you cannot assume anything about the state the other values returned.

There are a lot of type assertions which can fail in this patch, which will panic the program. More care needs to be made to avoid this.

Lastly, and most importantly. Please do not interpret my review as anything less than sheer delight that Go is being given a chance to show its worth to Openstack and I am committed to helping you show Go off to its full potential.

Thanks

Dave Cheney'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2015-05-01 09:24:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2015-05-01 09:29:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
initial import of go code

Better build instructions coming...  For now, get yourself a saio with go
installed then do something like:

    mkdir -p $GOPATH/src/github.com/openstack
    ln -s ~/swift $GOPATH/src/github.com/openstack/swift
    cd $GOPATH/src/github.com/openstack/swift/go
    make get test all

Change-Id: Ie26249355eccb7d1c37565c42cf5df028b54a95f

commit_message:
Revised service API to use ClusterPolicy module

Revised some service APIs related to cluster-policy bindings. The revise
is mainly targeted at get and list apis. For other operations, we still
need a cluster lock, so we still use the action model to achieve that.

Change-Id: I5a083809cf8c6e98f1c614b2a634c7dad9c05424

commit_message:
Switch tasks vs put on a boolean config flag

Rackspace's requirement for task-create is a choice that is orthogonal
to the v2 choice. Make that decision point clear. Also, rename the
hidden methods just so that we're clear on what's happening.

Update to a more recent version of os-client-config, since that also has
support for the task-create flag.

Depends-On: I2cdcfe302a73ebfa7f739399c1eeb3bc9f96ab3c
Change-Id: I72bb5992eeb116f1338a090d997893b9ae93050c

commit_message:
Fix invalid error message in neutron-cli

Error message displayed is not correct when we
provide invalid syntax for optional arguments
in neutron CLI
Closes-bug: 1438518

commit_message:
Honour ssh_connect_method in test_baremetal_server_ops

This commit changes test_baremetal_server_ops to add
a floating IP and check SSH connectivity with floating IP
only if [compute]ssh_connect_method == 'floating'.

Change-Id: I13bfd76522ebddd68fd347758e4861150ebedbea

commit_message:
Add a "plain" image type

Move the current "plain" version of the "hdp" type in an own type,
implemented for all the distros.  This way it is possible to easily
generate an image without any Hadoop component, without duplicating that
as "plain" subtype of existing types:

 $ diskimage-create.sh -p plain -i ubuntu|fedora|centos

Change-Id: I73ac2dc650b3050b1f49ea5b28e90a90bc08faf3
Closes-Bug: #1439368

commit_message:
Allow zk jobboard backend to take custom loader/dumpers

In order to allow for alternative non-json serialization
strategies allow for the zk jobboard backend to take a loader
and dumper backend keyword arguments which can be replaced
with msgpackutils or other serialization strategies.

Change-Id: I0a333407739e50e3f46642f877d4eb334e18f911

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-04 16:07:55.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed container user create issue

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

Change-Id: I46d8d407028485ad99f89347bf93354ed5043150
Closes-Bug: 1437054
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed container user create issue

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

Change-Id: I46d8d407028485ad99f89347bf93354ed5043150
Closes-Bug: 1437054

Currently, the event output is very resource-centric, despite
being scoped to the stack from an API path perspective.

This, combined with the fact that the stack updated_at timestamp
is only updated after a succesful update (ref bug #1193269) makes
it impossible to derive the time when an update started via any API.

This is a problem when trying to use the new hook/breakpoint API,
because it's necessary to poll for all events since the most recent
event started, disregarding any stale hook events from previous
updates (which may have failed or timed out without the hooks getting
cleared).

To work around this, add an event for each stack state transition,
such that you can detect the transition to UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS,
then use that event as a marker to get post-update-started events.

Without this (or some other way to determine when the stack update
started), the hooks pre-update functionality landed for kilo is
not really usable (particularly mechanically via scripts).

commit_message:
Generate stack events for stack state transitions

Currently, the event-list output is very resource-centric, despite
being scoped to the stack from an API path perspective.

This, combined with the fact that the stack updated_at timestamp
is only updated after a succesful update (ref bug #1193269) makes
it impossible to derive the time when an update started via any API.

This is a problem when trying to use the new hook/breakpoint API,
because it's necessary to poll for all events since the most recent
update started, disregarding any stale hook events from previous
updates (which may have failed or timed out without the hooks getting
cleared).

To work around this, add an event for each stack state transition,
such that you can detect the transition to UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS,
then use that event as a marker to get post-update-started events.

Without this (or some other way to determine when the stack update
started), the hooks pre-update functionality landed for kilo is
not really usable (particularly mechanically via scripts).

Change-Id: Idff342b3aecc2d145dfbc7c0f610ad0ca8e52c8b
Partial-Bug: #1448155

commit_message:
Fix exponentially growing AJAX updates for table rows

Schedule next table rows update only when the last row was
updated. Since unit-test for this fix relies on a blueprint
replace-qunit-tests-with-jasmine it is moved to a separate commit to
speed up this fix merge, see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179013/

Closes-Bug: #1263665
(cherry picked from commit ca090378b4875afebdebd67bdb457eebad6b2b7d)

Conflict Resolution Notes:
cherry-pick needed to have the old body of the complete: function
manually removed - it wasn't sure if it still belonged (resulting in
nearly duplicate code) or should be removed. I'm a bit surprised the
cherry-pick didn't auto-resolve.

Conflicts:
	horizon/static/horizon/js/horizon.tables.js

Change-Id: Id603a4fde5713d8f2b85b1dcf72c82c93a87c755

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Add Source Step Unit Tests

This patch adds unit tests for the source step.  These tests are focused
around the controller and its related components (no selenium tests or view
tests).

Co-Authored-By: Kelly Domico <kelly.domico@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Brian Tully <brian.tully@hp.com>

Change-Id: Ia31f043cf6f33808a9616388600f2a6810b82b07

commit_message:
Follow project renames

Rename keystoneclient-federation to saml2

Change Ie23f0c3a1f3e0a65baabe3dbd19091908da1aba2 renamed
python-keystoneclient-federation to python-keystoneclient-saml2, follow
the change in projects.txt.

Similar rally and congress have been renamed and need to be updated so
that the propose-requirements-update job works.

Change for rally: I4dbcab83747a48fe0beae4b5b09b51d3c35093c8
Change for congress: I4952ac54e8af3b69468315f6d4a16f5d6064bf33

Resort the project file alphabetically again.

Change-Id: Ib8a7f7b4538324c6b8aaf12f3f9260b9c3bcf76b

commit_message:
VMWare: Isolate unit tests from requests

The test_ipv6_host_read actually tested all the way down to the
requests url call, which means it's testing a lot of function
unrelated to the nova code. The interesting part of this test seems to
be that it builds the ipv6 url correctly.

Change this into an assert based on that url being correct. We still
need to mock out the http connection because that's done magically in
__init__.

Unblocks nova patches, which are failing on unit test since the latest
requests release and one of the function signatures changing.

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/virt/vmwareapi/test_read_write_util.py

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict is due to commit 80a63292c on master
not being in stable/kilo.

Change-Id: I8ae4cb00e63cbb0304210dba2cd4993016d852ba
Closes-bug: #1451389
(cherry picked from commit 117351d6c46bd6d00cc92fcd234d67a913833cbc)

commit_message:
update .tx/config to match Kilo Transifex resources

Transifex resource name for master branch is named as "djangopo"
which is not appropriate. For stable branch, we use
"openstack-auth-<release>" for Transifex resource name.

The corresponding Transifex resource is already prepared.

Change-Id: I4738db5402dddd8cf1c92af902aa261dc1aae6c1

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a

because there are other means to gain access to a container from

commit_message:
Fixed container user create issue

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

Change-Id: Id1d142dda967921450ddcecb0d7f70baf2218a42
Closes-Bug: 1437054

[{'created': '2015-04-28 09:58:19.000000000', 'message': "Fix intermittent container replicator test failure

Intermittent failure of this test could be due to
insufficient time elapsing between either the local
and remote db's being created or during the
debug_timing calls. This patch forces greater timestamp
separation and forces debug_timing to always log timings.

Also add message to the failign assertion so if this does
fail again we get some clue as to why.

Closes-Bug: 1369663

Change-Id: I4b69b2e759d586a14abd0931a68dbdf256d57c32
"}]
commit_message:
Fix intermittent container replicator test failure

Intermittent failure of this test could be due to
insufficient time elapsing between either the local
and remote db's being created or during the
debug_timing calls. This patch forces greater timestamp
separation and forces debug_timing to always log timings.

Also add message to the failign assertion so if this does
fail again we get some clue as to why.

Closes-Bug: 1369663

Change-Id: I4b69b2e759d586a14abd0931a68dbdf256d57c32

commit_message:
add script to generate release note email bodies

Produce the email body, ready to send (including headers), without
actually sending it. This gives us a chance to review the file
before sending, and then we can use another tool to actually send
the messages.

Change-Id: Ib53b0f9597a5508e53c4485fe690cd1299ad9e84

[{'created': '2015-03-13 16:29:29.000000000', 'message': "Fixed ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3 not supported by Python 2.7.9

Python 2.7.9 doesn't support ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3 by default anymore due to
security issues(POODLE attack). We should remove the usage of
ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3 in oslo-incubator.

This is a backport of: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162853/
which we need for Icehouse to run in Debian (in Jessie, each and every
package carry a specific patch, which isn't ideal at all...).

Change-Id: I41c6598cb874b79c391f8b4e4607b85c4660bd2f
Closes-Bug: 1395095
(cherry picked from commit de2d03023ec9e3fb35bdbfca970462f677cd2902)
"}]
commit_message:
Fixed ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3 not supported by Python 2.7.9

Python 2.7.9 doesn't support ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3 by default anymore due to
security issues(POODLE attack). We should remove the usage of
ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv3 in oslo-incubator.

This is a backport of: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162853/
which we need for Icehouse to run in Debian (in Jessie, each and every
package carry a specific patch, which isn't ideal at all...).

Change-Id: I41c6598cb874b79c391f8b4e4607b85c4660bd2f
Closes-Bug: 1395095
(cherry picked from commit de2d03023ec9e3fb35bdbfca970462f677cd2902)

commit_message:
Stop re-invoking pip

It turns out we need to just inject into install_requires so that pip's
egg_info processing will do the right thing for dependencies.

Change-Id: Ia6c4725b153b19c3d7e422b1fa62b70cded686e2

This change was made to ensure that PBR is using version < 0.11.0.
This is because changes in upstream PBR have made it impossible to
build contributing packages in heat and will likely impact other
services until the switch to liberty is in full effect. To ensure
consistent building of OpenStack packages PBR is now being installed
in the repo server containers which will ensure there are no
assumptions being made when creating python packages from OpenStack
contributing sources that may not be as well maintained as others.

Partial-bug: 1450733

'}]
commit_message:
Lock down PBR to < version 0.11.0

This change was made to ensure that PBR is using version < 0.11.0.
This is because changes in upstream PBR have made it impossible to
build contributing packages in heat and will likely impact other
services until the switch to liberty is in full effect. To ensure
consistent building of OpenStack packages PBR is now being installed
in the repo server containers which will ensure there are no
assumptions being made when creating python packages from OpenStack
contributing sources that may not be as well maintained as others.

Change-Id: I20c216543e63ef142119c2625fb219e030a708dd
Partial-bug: 1450733
(cherry picked from commit 688516acf0cd3f658b9c0c46ca877ca1b9b7edd3)

commit_message:
Change 'connection' default to sqlite:////var/lib/trove/trove.sqlite

Most of packages are running dbsync with default configuration while and
it fails because of default 'connection' parameter set to
sqlite:///trove_test.sqlite [1].

This patch changes the default to sqlite:////var/lib/trove/trove.sqlite

[1] http://paste.openstack.org/show/214767/
Closes-bug: #1451134

Change-Id: I7ca80543640949942427748852cda69cb37d1125

Add zookeeper tag in setup.cfg

Zookeeper driver.

commit_message:
Improve unit test for HashableDict

We have HashableDict introduced to network info storing, but hash
function of this implementation was never tested in unit tests.

Change-Id: Id48c9172ca63e19b397dc131d85ed631874142cd

commit_message:
Modify the agent and setup to accept custom plugins

For the agent I just modified to the config to use the new standard location for custom checks.
For monasca-setup I added automatic plugin detection.
Fixed config compare so order changes don't register as a config change.

Change-Id: I7ab17c894bb0496e30d7f5aa5a1b1cf9684bdf87

commit_message:
Use a socket timeout in get_auth

A previous change added socket timeouts, but they weren't plumbed
through to the get_auth code path. Make sure we're passing them along
everywhere.

Original-Author: Monty Taylor <mordred@inaugust.com>
Change-Id: I398241898248e66d1f8c436c8ed2ec7a0e9387f6
Closes-bug: 1447847

commit_message:
Add IP version support to all ip_lib code

Added an ip_version argument to IpNeighCommand.show() and
IpRouteCommand.pullup_route() to match other code in the file.

Change-Id: Ifdf2abc5a77f551223bad061a1abdc88695fa5f1

Change-Id: Ia07ced57af7a514ae3958356e5e310c2231d1633
"}]
commit_message:
update openstackclient requirement to 1.0.3

devstack on stable/kilo definitely doesn't work with 1.0.1, as it uses
commands that don't yet exist. 1.0.3 is what's currently being tested,
and 1.0.2 seems suspect.

Change-Id: Ia07ced57af7a514ae3958356e5e310c2231d1633

We might be able to work around this by changing the way Magnum is installed to make sure that it always ends up with a version of requests that works for it; but even if we do that, it seems that version 2.2.1 doesn't actually work for us (in all cases - it seems to be fine for some cases) any more. choose bump requests version to latest 2.6.0.

commit_message:
Bump requests version support

1. During the magnum gate job run, we use docker-py, and the pip
install default is
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/docker-py/1.1.0
which it requires requests >= 2.5.2
https://github.com/docker/docker-py/blob/master/setup.py

But in devstack stack.sh install in ubuntu, it uses requests 2.2.1
It seems use system package 2.2.1-1ubuntu0.2
http://logs.openstack.org/54/173154/1/check/check-functional-dsvm-magnum/7fa79f3/logs/dpkg-l.txt.gz

It then cause conflict for magnum, as docker-py require newer version than 2.2.1
Error logs as:
http://logs.openstack.org/54/173154/1/check/check-functional-dsvm-magnum/7fa79f3/console.html#_2015-04-14_05_45_54_797

For magnum code refer:
https://github.com/openstack/magnum/blob/master/requirements.txt

2. We once tried to use older docker-py(0.7~1.0) version, but in tox -e py27
the pip install requests is latest 2.6.0, which broke docker-py which requests
requests >= 2.2.1, < 2.5.0

As magnum depends on global requirements for devstack, So we only have to
choose bump requests version to latest 2.6.0.

Change-Id: Ic55f1d70093472e59417d215bb3f0c5276a678de

commit_message:
clean up logging around run_process

We do a bunch of exec magic unwind in run_process that leads to a lot
of confusing lines in the logs under xtrace. Instead, disable xtrace
through these parts to ensure that the flow at the end of the day
makes more sense.

Change-Id: I91e02465240e704a1a0c0036f5073c0295be018e

commit_message:
Don't use SessionClient for version-list API

The endpoint of version API doesn't contain "/v2/{project-id}" and it is
just "/". SessionClient is based on the endpoint "/v2/{project-id}/...",
so this patch makes a client use a raw url for version-list API.

Change-Id: I53f2afacce2dda14ac9761e824b48887f7c192f9
Closes-Bug: #1444235

[{'created': '2015-04-28 16:18:01.000000000', 'message': 'Fix RBD delete image on creation failure

When an exception rises on RBD store while adding/creating an image, and
the image has already been created, this new image is not properly
deleted as it should be.

Fault lies in incorrect call to Store._delete_image method, as it is
called with the wrong arguments.

Change-Id: Ib74f7eafbb04ab893039b480a7d3eaa15e7d59d1
Closes-Bug: #1449639
'}]
commit_message:
Fix RBD delete image on creation failure

When an exception rises on RBD store while adding/creating an image, and
the image has already been created, this new image is not properly
deleted as it should be.

Fault lies in incorrect call to Store._delete_image method, as it is
called with the wrong arguments.

Change-Id: Ib74f7eafbb04ab893039b480a7d3eaa15e7d59d1
Closes-Bug: #1449639

commit_message:
Disable voting for puppet-syntax-future on havana/icehouse

We recently enabled voting for puppet-syntax-future jobs.
The recent rspec refactor & update has not been backported until
stable/icehouse and stable/havana, so until we figure out how to deal
with these stable branches and rspec version, let's disable the job
on icehouse and havana to unblock stable CI.

Change-Id: Iea11c4b5809cd6bf82ddcd49db7e10540bcc3714
Partial-bug: #1451460

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-04 16:23:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed container user create issue

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

Change-Id: I81d0e8b0d8e9e431cd8eebd43ceaffab7e61b207
Closes-Bug: 1437054
(cherry pick from commit 8efb09f90dae73a21ec3dc21842fe28e668ead39)
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed container user create issue

This patch resolves an issue where the LXC container create user
password is being hard coded due to how the default LXC container
template is being used. The template allows for a container to be
created without specifying a password at create time however when
doing this the default LXC template will create a user and a
password based on the linux distribution's name. This means that
all users of a "ubuntu" template will have a "ubuntu" user which
will have a "ubuntu" password. While the container user must exist
the password does not need to be known to the end user/deployer
because there are other means to gain access to a container from
within the host. So to correct this issue for all deployers as
well as all future deployments this patch ensures that the container
user is created with a random password and provides for an additional
tag to allow the deployer to regenerate the password at will.

Change-Id: I81d0e8b0d8e9e431cd8eebd43ceaffab7e61b207
Closes-Bug: 1437054
(cherry pick from commit 8efb09f90dae73a21ec3dc21842fe28e668ead39)

commit_message:
Convert node_set_provision_state to task

Changed node_set_provision_state to utilize a task instead of a
direct ironicclient library API call.

Additionally added basic unit tests for activate_node,
deactivate_node, and node_set_provision_state.

Change-Id: I036f1e87310e48727ef4e402e475c77cd014e6b1

by other get_<resource>() methods.

appropriate name, as it returns the current session endpoints.

commit_message:
Rename get_endpoint() to get_session_endpoint()

In a subsequent change, we will add Keystone endpoint methods.
In that change, get_endpoint() would return an endpoint by id, as done
by other get_<resource>() methods.
This change renames get_endpoint() in OpenStackCloud with a more
appropriate name, as it returns the current session endpoints.

Change-Id: Ie91f97457fb164255d2adf4e84c1b1f729e797b0

commit_message:
Configure cinder-backup for Ceph backend

As the cinder::backup class doesn't configure any backend by default,
cinder::backup::ceph has to be defined explicitly. Additionally
cinder-backup requires a seperate client and pool for storing backups.
The user has to have read access to regular cinder's pool in order to
actually backup anything.

Change-Id: I445a03840a7ef17a799d99f161d874df99821eef
Closes-Bug: 1446593

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Iae62b48993eef3b31420f8cc245a55f5e303c4fc

commit_message:
Add xags argument to get_active_vioses

The get_active_vioses operation was added to the vios.py recently.
However, all calls down to it were with xags=None.  Most of the
invocations want the active VIOS with the appropriate XAGs.

This change set allows for an optional parameter to get the XAGs.

Change-Id: Ied9b264b8062aa7d3594101ee5d91c9fcff98c68

commit_message:
Remove traits from Response, add adapter to bld()s

Recently pypowervm removed the traits parameter from the Response
constructor, and added an adapter parameter to the various wrapper bld
methods.

Change-Id: I80fa269112ed305225d80f2cad84f80f937f44d3

commit_message:
Use pymemcache pooled client

A thread-safe pooled client was added in 1.2.9
so we no longer need to subclass to add on thread
safety to achieve the same result.

Change-Id: Ida963da86dc2fb56580801f549ca557b76dd1c73

commit_message:
Remove support for sqlalchemy in devstack

Zaqar doesn't support sqlalchemy for the dataplane anymore. This patch
removes it. Future patches will bring it back to support the management
plane.

Change-Id: If464f1b6ba5bda84654ff70f19ea891c99ba92e3
Depends-On: If5c91ebe136017cea2eeecf62a580d050e49617d

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-09 12:43:16.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for Glance RBD backend

This patch adds support for a new GlanceBackend setting
which can be set to one of swift, rbd, or file to control

commit_message:
Add support for Glance RBD backend

This patch adds support for a new GlanceBackend setting
which can be set to one of swift, rbd, or file to control
which Glance backend is configured for use by default.

Change-Id: Id6a3fbc3477e85e8e2446e3dc13d424f9535d0ff

commit_message:
New API allow clients to execute a pipeline of commands

Currently, several clients of execute() who wish to execute a pipeline
of commands need to do this using a literal string and specifying
"shell=True" in the invocation of subprocess.Popen(). This change
allows users to construct a pipeline of commands, potentially
including sudo, and execute that entire pipeline without requiring
shell=True.

The new API execute_pipeline() takes a subset of the parameters that
execute() accepts and constructs and executes the pipeline, returning
the stdout, stderr and returncode. Similar to execute() this API will
log some information after sanitizing through strutils.mask_password()
and will return stdout and stderr that have been similarly
sanitized.

Also, similar to execute() this API computes total time and logs it in
the same way that execute() does.

I have also reviewed the package 'sarge' and a very quick assessment
indicates that it isn't as fast as the present implementation and in
the short term, I think an implementation similar to execute() would
be preferable. I'll look to wrap sarge and potentially reimplement
processutils based on it independently.

Test cases have been proposed as well.

Change-Id: I8b911a41acdd5cd63c0ae66c359c9e0fbc148fea
Closes-Bug: #1413751

commit_message:
Have run_watchers take a timeout and respect it

Like the rest of the functions in coordinators they
should try to take and respect timeouts wherever possible,
so the run_watcher method (which calls into various async
functions) should also take a timeout, and try to respect it
where possible.

Change-Id: I2558a54f69dc5033c3a73351c4f7fbff7bdd6297

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-03 17:32:30.000000000', 'message': 'Use dhcp_gateway for admin network GW if it's set

We have a special setting "DHCP Gateway" in fuelmenu
(which is stored as 'dhcp_gateway' in astute.yaml) and
was added in order to set default GW for PXE/admin
network. Use master node IP as gateway only when that
parameter is not set.

Change-Id: I1f7caad9c52feeba8c19ef800351ab0d90c47d08
Closes-bug: #1451222
'}]
commit_message:
Use dhcp_gateway for admin network GW if it's set

We have a special setting "DHCP Gateway" in fuelmenu
(which is stored as 'dhcp_gateway' in astute.yaml) and
was added in order to set default GW for PXE/admin
network. Use master node IP as gateway only when that
parameter is not set.

Change-Id: I1f7caad9c52feeba8c19ef800351ab0d90c47d08
Closes-bug: #1451222

commit_message:
sqlalchemy: name FK constraints

We didn't name the foreign keys constraint which is going to make
upgrade very painful in the future. Let's do that right now before
having 1.0 and freezing our schema.

Change-Id: I5b6902b9db7d8f74984df35b149bf0eb5d825b2c
(cherry picked from commit 9a684c02dec30e68e2db5ca3a2efb86071a126d3)

commit_message:
Updated merge that avoid duplicating named instances in a config.

Skip config writing and restart if there are no changes to the config.
Added names to various config instances to aid in repeat runs of setup.

Change-Id: Idd29f8abe29b4889868a9044116cbdcdfdba6262

commit_message:
Make ZeroMQ driver work without eventlet

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+spec/zmq-work-without-eventlet

Oslo.messaging ZeroMQ driver lacks the ability to work without eventlet.
:meth:`eventlet.spawn` is heavily used across the driver with no alternatives.

Provide an alternative way of calling methods to use with blocking executor.

Change-Id: I8d3697b7395236992e23a94edd9f10be3410b108

commit_message:
remove metadata_proxy_local filters for rootwrap

With the dependent patch Iade8b5b09bb53018485c85f8372fb94dbc2ad2da,
/usr/local/bin is added to exec_dirs in rootwrap.conf. Therefore, these
filters are no longer needed for devstack use case.

Depends-On: Iade8b5b09bb53018485c85f8372fb94dbc2ad2da
Change-Id: I98bff3cc679dfe19315f2b9b028ff48e4296e0de

commit_message:
Rename service to zaqar

Instead of using `zaqar-server` as the service name in devstack, use
zaqar. This will allow for future services to be added.

Change-Id: I65667da3783130876ed781b2659000b82fa15e37
Depends-On: If5c91ebe136017cea2eeecf62a580d050e49617d

commit_message:
Fixes the unsafe mocking in test_dbaas

test_dbaas.MySqlAppMockTest.test_secure_with_mycnf_error
contains a mocked entry for operating_system.service_discovery.
This entry is unsafe and it has not been unmocked, also

It looks to me the primary reason for this bug: 1450789.

Made the mocking safe by the usage of "with patch.object(..." usage

Change-Id: Ib0f18b65be04490f8f60ff878a7af512a5e9bed5
Closes-Bug: #1450789

commit_message:
sqlalchemy: name FK constraints

We didn't name the foreign keys constraint which is going to make
upgrade very painful in the future. Let's do that right now before
having 1.0 and freezing our schema.

Change-Id: I5b6902b9db7d8f74984df35b149bf0eb5d825b2c

commit_message:
add bagpipe driver and agent

including:
- add a README-bagpipe.rst for the bagpipe driver
- add setup.cf entry points
- extend devstack plugin so that the modified agent
  can be enabled with Q_AGENT=bagpipe-openvswitch

Change-Id: I6cd18eca77e5f2b43b0b15d141637cef6db044e4

commit_message:
Verify that each step provisioning went well

Use the serverspec hook to verify that the previous provisioning step
left the platform in an expected and correct state. It is a dependency
to go and run the next step.

Change-Id: Ic63a62b655f3dc221c9462cb555e878d4ad8b57c

commit_message:
Implement group related methods for LDAP backend

This patch implements three functions, empty in the LDAP backend,
which are necessary to obtain information about groups,
such as roles, projects and domains of the groups.

These are the functions:

- list_domain_ids_for_user
- list_domain_ids_for_groups

Change-Id: Ie0e2ad9b24add9e3a27a251e089e12acf36ce933
Closes-Bug: #1333712

commit_message:
Temporarily add trove plugin configuration

In order to move the trove configuration from devstack to trove,
we need to enable the plugin.  This should be done in a job config,
but since that can not be tested with a change and will break if
it lands before the plugin is moved, enable it in devstack-gate
to facilitate the transition.

Once the transition is complete, this can be removed.

Change-Id: I3506dec0e6097f9c2e9267110fdfb768faa23c85
Depends-On: I15667bf9c063e886755aef29056ef0028cbb1080

[{'created': '2015-05-03 18:14:22.000000000', 'message': 'Pass the flag for Identity v3 API only jobs

When DEVSTACK_GATE_IDENTITY_V3_ONLY is set to 1,
pass it as IDENTITY_V3_ONLY=True in the devstack
local.conf file.

Devstack will:
* Disable the v2 API in Keystone paste config;
* Set Tempest to skip Identity v2 tests and use
  v3 auth tokens to run all the other tests;
* Set Horizon to use v3 API and v3 auth tokens.

Change-Id: I345170430ced6c1443292a8f3dc3b9e6c105ee70
'}]
commit_message:
Pass the flag for Identity v3 API only jobs

When DEVSTACK_GATE_IDENTITY_V3_ONLY is set to 1,
pass it as IDENTITY_V3_ONLY=True in the devstack
local.conf file.

Devstack will:
* Disable the v2 API in Keystone paste config;
* Set Tempest to skip Identity v2 tests and use
  v3 auth tokens to run all the other tests;
* Set Horizon to use v3 API and v3 auth tokens.

Change-Id: I345170430ced6c1443292a8f3dc3b9e6c105ee70

commit_message:
Allow overwriting sphinx builder from command line

The build_sphinx setuptools command supports selection of a builder.
Support the behaviour of being able to explicitely select any builder
available to sphinx via "python setup.py build_sphinx -b linkcheck", not
just one of the builders specified in the configuration file.

Change-Id: I4c7ddcaf413e1bcc72550b3d920f8a777a710c97

Update recent Ironic exceptions

Update of the recent changes landed for Ironic so that the returned
exception messages are converted to a string like the other returned
exception messages in Shade.

commit_message:
Enhance error message in update_machine

Updated error messages through the use of try/except blocks in
update_machine in order to help a user identify what the possible
cause of a failure could be without studying the code.

Change-Id: I04db479ce1b25aadd710cde5d90fe71fa528869b

commit_message:
incorrect SSL header used in example config

Updating the example local_settings.py to have HTTP_X_FORWARDED_PROTO in
addition to HTTP_X_FORWARDED_PROTOCOL.  Only Django 1.4 uses
HTTP_X_FORWARDED_PROTOCOL and Django 1.5 and up uses HTTP_X_FORWARDED_PROTO
which is probably the majority of installations.

Closes-bug: #1446836
Change-Id: Iebb854cf5e5586c6613b5755d4641ee896056334

commit_message:
Fix can_send_version to check against the base client version

Up until now clients would happily pass any version as long as there is
no version_cap specifed, disregarding the version of the Target that was
passed in to the constructor.

This now makes it fail if the version is higher than the one passed on
construction. A sideffect of this change is that now specifying the cap
that is higher than the version of the target passed in is that it will
always fail the can_send_version test.

Closes-bug: #1330916

Change-Id: Ic4f1b46bb331c3af9d041bc47fecf1f9bdb96871

[{'created': '2014-07-04 08:02:01.000000000', 'message': "Add heartbeat support to kombu

This change adds heartbeat support for kombu by passing in heartbeat parameter
of default value 60 second and adding a thread(eventlet) that spawns after heartbeat/2
seconds to check for the connection.

This is a critical bug fix for cases where network connections are not reliable.
One of my test scenario had a NAT between nova-compute and the nova-conductor/nova-scheduler.
NAT devices are known to drop idle connections without telling corresponding parties of
the state of the connection. This behavior caused interesting 'hung' operation on nova side.

Here are the details:
Setup:

Nova-Conduct/Scheduler are running on a machine 'P' along with Broker
Nova-compute C is running on a virtual machine local at my workplace behind a NAT.
Both P, C are using Kombu 3.0.16 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/kombu)

P creates a 'topic' exchange and create a Queue (nova_compute_<id>) which needs acknowledgements.
C waits for the message upon arrival sends an ack back to B.

Scenarios:

Positive:
P and C are connected to B, P publishes messages, C receives it and everything works fine.

Negative:
While C is connected to B,

step-1) I disconnect the 'virtual network' which disconnects the virtual machine C is running on.
So effectively C is not reachable anymore. (This should be similar to unplugging network cable to a machine)

At this point of time, I observed the following on broker machine:

rabbitmqctl list_connections name state timeout : it shows the connection between the B and C as running, timeout value=0
rabbitmqctl list_queues name messages_ready messages_unacknowledged: shows name and both ready and unacked messages =0

step-2) I then publish a message from P on the Q.

Now

rabbitmqctl list_connections name state timeout : it shows the connection between the B and C as running, timeout value=0
rabbitmqctl list_queues name messages_ready messages_unacknowledged: shows name and both ready =0 and unacked messages =1

step-3) I then publish another message from P on the Q.

Now

rabbitmqctl list_connections name state timeout : it shows the connection between the B and C as running, timeout value=0
rabbitmqctl list_queues name messages_ready messages_unacknowledged: shows name and both ready =0 and unacked messages =2

step-4) I plug 'connect' the network for C again but I never see the messages on the C they remain in the unacked state > 8 hrs (I didn't check after that).

Solution:
After the fix, the timeout value in Step-1,2,3 = 60 and step-4 succeeds and the messages are delivered.

Some references:

http://kombu.readthedocs.org/en/latest/reference/kombu.connection.html
https://www.rabbitmq.com/amqp-0-9-1-reference.html
https://github.com/celery/py-amqp/

Change-Id: Iee6866890aa24f46f03daae7e7f4b5d2c99dde65

commit_message:
Add heartbeat support to kombu

This change adds heartbeat support for kombu by passing in heartbeat parameter
of default value 60 second and adding a thread(eventlet) that spawns after heartbeat/2
seconds to check for the connection.

This is a critical bug fix for cases where network connections are not reliable.
One of my test scenario had a NAT between nova-compute and the nova-conductor/nova-scheduler.
NAT devices are known to drop idle connections without telling corresponding parties of
the state of the connection. This behavior caused interesting 'hung' operation on nova side.

Here are the details:
Setup:

Nova-Conduct/Scheduler are running on a machine 'P' along with Broker
Nova-compute C is running on a virtual machine local at my workplace behind a NAT.
Both P, C are using Kombu 3.0.16 (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/kombu)

P creates a 'topic' exchange and create a Queue (nova_compute_<id>) which needs acknowledgements.
C waits for the message upon arrival sends an ack back to B.

Scenarios:

Positive:
P and C are connected to B, P publishes messages, C receives it and everything works fine.

Negative:
While C is connected to B,

step-1) I disconnect the 'virtual network' which disconnects the virtual machine C is running on.
So effectively C is not reachable anymore. (This should be similar to unplugging network cable to a machine)

At this point of time, I observed the following on broker machine:

rabbitmqctl list_connections name state timeout : it shows the connection between the B and C as running, timeout value=0
rabbitmqctl list_queues name messages_ready messages_unacknowledged: shows name and both ready and unacked messages =0

step-2) I then publish a message from P on the Q.

Now

rabbitmqctl list_connections name state timeout : it shows the connection between the B and C as running, timeout value=0
rabbitmqctl list_queues name messages_ready messages_unacknowledged: shows name and both ready =0 and unacked messages =1

step-3) I then publish another message from P on the Q.

Now

rabbitmqctl list_connections name state timeout : it shows the connection between the B and C as running, timeout value=0
rabbitmqctl list_queues name messages_ready messages_unacknowledged: shows name and both ready =0 and unacked messages =2

step-4) I plug 'connect' the network for C again but I never see the messages on the C they remain in the unacked state > 8 hrs (I didn't check after that).

Solution:
After the fix, the timeout value in Step-1,2,3 = 60 and step-4 succeeds and the messages are delivered.

Some references:

http://kombu.readthedocs.org/en/latest/reference/kombu.connection.html
https://www.rabbitmq.com/amqp-0-9-1-reference.html
https://github.com/celery/py-amqp/

Change-Id: Iee6866890aa24f46f03daae7e7f4b5d2c99dde65

commit_message:
Trap formatting errors

Trap errors when trying to use translated messages as format strings so
translations don't break applications. Log the error, with the format
string (without interpolated values) and the original message so a bug
report can include it to make fixing the translation easier.

Change-Id: I4cd385dffc0b23c7cc6a663dd1700ac14a84c5d2
Closes-bug: #1339337

Made reply handling code much simpler.
As a bonus overall performance of calls is doubled.

Removed one of the test cases that tested logic of previous

commit_message:
Brand new ReplyWaiter based on futures

Made reply handling code much simpler.
As a bonus overall performance of calls is doubled.

Removed one of the test cases that tested logic of previous
ReplyWaiter. Right now it's not needed since we don't have complex
conditions to care about.

New ReplyWaiter code is tested indirectly in test_impl_rabbit
test_send_receive test.

Change-Id: Ieba012e67a9857ca84cd5af4d3aed31ee09f6142

I'm still not sure how this change will allow for a better executor model, perhaps your executor should return futures? This will allow for using either concurrent.futures or asyncio.futures (or something else). If the executors are expected to return a future object, that would I believe help in getting to asyncio or other..."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-07-28 15:56:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(5 comments)

Some answers inline.

Currently executor doesn't need to return anything since server doesn't care about executors reply.
It makes executor simpler since:

* executor no longer cares about reading messages from server
* executor call dispatcher in a single call and doesn't have to implement __enter__ __exit__ calls to make dispatcher work properly"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-07-29 03:16:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

I agree with the change and the cleanup of the executor class. I just wonder that the change to make executor not return anything is actually the thing we want to be doing. I don't see the harm in returning a future from __call__ (or whatever it will be named). Imho assuming nobody will ever care about the result is/will be a limitation and we might as well not limit ourselves from the start..."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-07-29 04:23:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-07-29 09:14:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

>I just wonder that the change to make executor not return anything is actually the thing we want to be doing.

Why would we want to return something from executor to the server? And how server should use this result?

Currently dispatcher calls ack/requeue/reply on message object. Could you please describe some use case where explicit return would be usefull?'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-07-30 05:58:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Just thinking, being that its a server, wouldn't server want to know whether it sent something (or at least have the capability to know this?). If nothing is ever returned then there isn't a possibility that it could ever know it wasn't sent. Maybe can be changed in the future, but it would seem like typical servers actually would care about whatever they have sent off."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-07-31 14:52:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-31 14:52:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Moved main loop to server class

This will allow us to simplify dispatchers, executors and provide means
to implement custom Server class if needed.

Corresponding spec - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105796/

Change-Id: Ifbc135ac94579ec9412843b87e069956dc353552

(1 comment)

I'm not entirely convinced there is a need for the credit batching, but it doesn't hurt either. I do find the configuration of it slightly unintuitive (to me it would be more intuitive to set the maximum, and then leave the driver to refresh when it gets to half of that, rather than configure the minimum and have the driver double it) however that is not a big issue and likely just a peculiarity of how my mind works(!). I don't imagine anyone will be configuring these values for a while anyway - they are really configuration only because we aren't sure what the best value should be yet."}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-10-13 14:41:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Ah, yes - what I did with those settings really isn't natural, the code just came out that way (says something about the way I think, I'm afraid! :)

I'll need to clarify the overall behavior a bit better - as you point out, this patch doesn't implement end-to-end flow control, just the flow on the connection from the messaging service (broker) to the oslo.messaging clients.

The important effect of the patch is to control the amount of internal queuing of received messages that is done in the oslo.messaging client."}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-10-13 17:33:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-10-13 17:34:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

[{'created': '2014-10-10 15:19:13.000000000', 'message': "Implement message flow control using link credit

This change implements a scheme for managing link credit for consumer
links.  There are two different link use cases in this driver, each
of which employs its own credit management scheme:

The per-connection RPC reply link: the RPC sender is rate limited
given the synchronous nature of the RPC implementation.  Also, we need
to avoid having a 'slow' RPC client block an RPC server. Therefore the
shared RPC reply link does not backpressure senders.  It maintains a
credit level in the range of [$reply_credit ... 2*$reply_credit]: a
batch of $reply_credit credits are granted whenever the current credit
level drops below $reply_credit.

The per-target RPC server links: the RPC servers need to be able to
backpressure the RPC clients should the server's backlog of incoming
RPC request messages becomes 'excessive'.  This is done by
implementing a high/low watermark on the queue of incoming RPC request
messages.  When the number of queued RPC request messages becomes
greater than $listener_max_backlog, the driver will stop granting
credit on all receive links associated with the RPC server's
subscription to its target.  When the number of queued RPC requests
drops to less than $listener_low_backlog, credit will resume being
granted to the receive links.  The scheme for maintaining credit on
the topic's receive links (when not blocking) is similar to the method
used for the per-connection RPC reply link: the credit level on all
links is maintained in the range [$subscription_credit
... 2*$subscription_credit].

Change-Id: If2a00139123d069d6968d6451d974d8aa183dcc4
Closes-Bug: #1367911

commit_message:
Implement message flow control using link credit

This change implements a scheme for managing link credit for consumer
links.  There are two different link use cases in this driver, each
of which employs its own credit management scheme:

The per-connection RPC reply link: the RPC sender is rate limited
given the synchronous nature of the RPC implementation.  Also, we need
to avoid having a 'slow' RPC client block an RPC server. Therefore the
shared RPC reply link does not backpressure senders.  It maintains a
credit level in the range of [$reply_credit/2 ... $reply_credit].

The per-target RPC server links: the RPC servers need to be able to
backpressure the broker should the server's backlog of incoming RPC
request messages becomes 'excessive'.  This is done by implementing a
high/low watermark on the queue of incoming RPC request messages.
When the number of queued RPC request messages becomes greater than
$listener_max_backlog, the driver will stop granting credit on all
receive links associated with the RPC server's subscription to its
target.  When the number of queued RPC requests drops to less than
$listener_low_backlog, credit will resume being granted to the receive
links.  The scheme for maintaining credit on the topic's receive links
(when not blocking) is similar to the method used for the
per-connection RPC reply link: the credit level on all links is
maintained in the range [$subscription_credit/2
... $subscription_credit].

Change-Id: If2a00139123d069d6968d6451d974d8aa183dcc4
Closes-Bug: #1367911

commit_message:
Remove set_time_override in timeutils

The set_time_override function in timeutils was written as a
helper function to mock utcnow for unittests before 'mock' was
generally used. Now that we have mock and fixture, we no longer
need to use it.

Change-Id: I4d4af4933237b2ab424329c66ce792e7cb4f2a00
Closes-Bug: #1266962

commit_message:
Check cli parameter when checking if the option is already registered

Currently, if we register some options using both register_opts()
and register_cli_opts(). The register_cli_opts() will ignore as
the option is though already registerd. Hence no option will
appear with '-h' parameter, and the option is not registered as
cli options.

I fix this bug by checking the cli parameter passed to the
_is_opt_registered() method.

Change-Id: Ib096157ea05a6bfb7a8da812a8f9190d925da88b
Closes-Bug: 1363808

thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-07-03 17:07:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The only difference between rpartition and partition is whether we want to banish dotted options or dotted groups from interpolation. I think dotted groups are more useful than dotted options because you can use full module/class name as a group name. That's why I used rpartition.

Still that doesn't matter because support for dotted groups/options is nowhere mentioned in docs and the fact that this code supports groups is just a side effect of how it's written.

Moreover this feature will hardly ever be used for dotted groups since they are not used in OpenStack in the first place.

Flavio, the issue of verifying whether there are dots in group or option name is not related to this change. Do you insist on your -1?"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-07-03 21:24:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> The only difference between rpartition and partition is whether we want to banish dotted options or dotted groups from interpolation. I think dotted groups are more useful than dotted options because you can use full module/class name as a group name. That's why I used rpartition.

This, precisely, makes my -1 valid. Since, as Mark mentioned, there's an ambiguity and it's not clear what the right thing to do here is. I'm personally not happy with letting this patch landing without clearing out what our plan in this regard is. For example, if we let the patch land and then decide to not allow dots in group/option names, we'll have to come back here and change it too.

I'm not saying this patch can't land w/o fixing the current status, I'm just saying we need to be clear on what we want. I think it's find to have a reserved character for the library and raising an exception, as Mark mentioned, seems to be a good way to start moving towards that plan and also a good way to remove the ambiguity here.

> Still that doesn't matter because support for dotted groups/options is nowhere mentioned in docs and the fact that this code supports groups is just a side effect of how it's written.

This is more a problem than a relief, TBH. It seems to me this is the right moment to clear this.

> Moreover this feature will hardly ever be used for dotted groups since they are not used in OpenStack in the first place.

We were very close to use them in marconi but then decided to use colons. I agree it's likely not being used anywhere in OpenStack but the library is also consumed outside OpenStack, which means we need to be extra careful since we don't know who's using it nor how they are using it. :("}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-07-04 11:29:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Dots in section names are a kind of a standard way of implementing hierarchy in the configuration file. commit_message:
Allow to reference values outside DEFAULT in substitution

This change allows use to reference values in form ${group.name}. User
also can reference values from the same group by omitting group name:
${.name}. Usage example:

  [DEFAULT]
  someservice_url=${someservice.url}
  [someservice]
  url=http://${.host}:${.port}
  host=someservice.example.com
  port=80

Change-Id: Iac68943e83975ac40afbc20a79a4c12bb1dcef34

commit_message:
Support groups in option value interpolation

This change enhances the option value interpolation feature to support
interpolation across groups. The template syntax to reference an option
in another group is ${group.option} (the brackets are required).

Change-Id: I98dae021852f1ac646bd17f44d96717c7687fec8
Implements: blueprint group-option-interpolation

commit_message:
Handle WSME errors in clients

WSME errors contains ``faultcode`` and ``faultstring``, plus an
optional ``debuginfo`` attribute.

Change-Id: Ic16661d3d266770383f786bd3ade68c629bf758f
Closes-bug: #1354470

commit_message:
Moved main loop to server class

This will allow us to simplify dispatchers, executors and provide means
to implement custom Server class if needed.

Restored from: Ifbc135ac94579ec9412843b87e069956dc353552

Corresponding spec - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/133668/

Change-Id: If045d5199f2f743c0e4f0249928ca697b7e3fdeb

commit_message:
Adds message security plugins

This adds an optional plugin framework for message security. It
also provides two plugin implementations, a dummy pass through
and one for using kite.

Change-Id: Icbed9d0aee4c84bb396f58bcb7516797a97a515b
Implements: blueprint trusted-messaging

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

I understand your concern, but note that the code isn't just testing for a colon or equals, it's also looking for a space to follow.

When I was looking into what values are likely to be in a config file, I found MAC addresses and database connection strings that use colons and/or equals signs.  I also considered URLs.  In all cases that I found, no values had a colon or equals sign followed by a space.  URLs aren't _supposed_ to have spaces in them at all, but I suppose it's possible.

My thinking is that the parser shouldn't error out just because a line in the config file starts with a space.  I think that scenario is very likely, and quite a bit more likely that encountering a value that has a colon or equals sign followed by a space.

I had to really dig to find anything about what the config files are expected to contain and found that it's not very defined at this point.

I just thought we could take care of the reported error with little to no risk of breaking the parsing of config files.

If it would help, I could add test cases for secondary values being URLs, DB connection strings and MAC addresses.

Just let me know.  :)"}, {'account_id': 11913, 'date': '2014-07-26 16:20:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Removing a hash from a line in a config file without also removing
the leading space on the line leads to a parsing error.  The
problem occurs because any line starting with a space is assumed
to be the second parameter in a 'multiline' key/value assignment.

The proposed fix allows for the multiline assignment and allows
any line to have leading whitespace by requiring than any
additional lines in a multiline assignment do not have colons or
equals signs.  If a line does have a colon or equals sign, it's
considered a new key/value assignment.

If and when configuration files are more standardized, this
parsing behavior should be revisited.  At this point, though, it
fixes the reported bug and passes all the other parsing tests as
well.

commit_message:
Allow parsing of key/value lines with leading whitespace

Removing a hash from a line in a config file without also removing
the leading space on the line leads to a parsing error.  The
problem occurs because any line starting with a space is assumed
to be the second parameter in a 'multiline' key/value assignment.

The proposed fix allows for the multiline assignment and allows
any line to have leading whitespace by requiring than any
additional lines in a multiline assignment do not have colons or
equals signs.  If a line does have a colon or equals sign, it's
considered a new key/value assignment.

If and when configuration files are more standardized, this
parsing behavior should be revisited.  At this point, though, it
fixes the reported bug and passes all the other parsing tests as
well.

Closes-Bug: 1266832

Change-Id: Ie20fd3b99bb757c74ee00012539fc71e0d68fc16

commit_message:
Warn if new and deprecated options are both present

Its possibly a misconfiguration if both new and deprecated
versions of an option are configured at the same time.  The
recommendation has been to log a warning when this is detected.

I've included group, name, and value for any such options as
debugging aid.

Change-Id: I10951d0ec4df2688540e95eef3dd7a913a5da4b9
Closes-Bug: 1319868

commit_message:
Add load_config_file function

When developing I4b860e3f7901b00b1c78f7df1f2219132f347239 I found it
difficult provide a small, additional config-file snippet that
unit-tests could use to test the new config-option provided.

My suggestion is to provide a load_config_file() function that simply
parses adds a given config-file into the existing name-space.

I think this would enhance the ability of certain unit-tests, such as
for the change above, to be "end-to-end" ... that is to test the
values are read correctly from the config file into oslo.config and
used correctly in the program.

Change-Id: I26f5132e6323340617dd9448661e325ff3f509e3

commit_message:
Add a ProxyConfigOpts derivative (WIP)

Add a new subclass of _CachedConfigOpts that can ask a provided
object for values (that provided object could be a dictionary,
a webservice, something else...), it will also be able to notify
some provided object when options are registered, unregistered and
so-on (so that the provided object may adjust its own information
if it needs to).

An example that shows the usage of this is at:

http://paste.ubuntu.com/9113641/

With output at:

http://paste.ubuntu.com/9113668/

Change-Id: I21b1914b490f3ac5722a5263a764c5eb60a4073e

commit_message:
Refactor config opts, deriving from common base (WIP)

Start to shift the functionality of the config opts class
into a base class that allows for other implementations of
config opts that can provide there own implementations of
the base abstract methods (perhaps providing a '_do_get' that
fetchs from a remote source, or from a dictionary, or from
elsewhere).

This is a first step at decoupling oslo.config from being so
tied to CLI and config file parsing, extraction... so that in
the future more flexible and alternative sources can easily
co-exist.

Change-Id: Id2e194fbdf7310c3cf704f1a1b96f07292420d3b

commit_message:
Add an option for late acknowledgement in RPC

In order to use RPC cast as a simple work queue, the RPC dispatcher
must be able to send the ACK only after it's finished executing
the callback, so the message can be delivered to another server
in case this one crashes mid-callback.

The parameter is optional and the default behaviour doesn't change
so it won't impact the current use of RPC in OpenStack projects.

Change-Id: Idaa03271dc4b054979df276ca47b583900b5062b
Closes-bug: #1350212

commit_message:
`publisher`function separated into ZmqProxy method

In the `consume` method of ZmqProxy class declared a function named
`publisher`. This function contains reach socket data sending logic. This
function became the instance method named `_publisher`.

Such an approach is much easier to test and improve logic of the
function.

Change-Id: I769f0616726785a6b0e60d84072f7446b5a29e34

commit_message:
Helper method to check and restrict socket name

ZMQ IPC socket paths limited to 107 characters in length. Thus we need
to check and restrict it.
Closes-Bug: #1367614

commit_message:
Topic object

Topic manipulations are significant part of Zero MQ driver. All of these
actions were performed in-line as string operations. This kind of design
is very difficult to debug and modify. We to have a single entry point
for topic to reduce the described issues.

* Created Topic object with appropriate methods to manipulate and
control topic value.
* Extended Target object to use Topic object with normal Target
features.
* To restrict and standardize topic length used md5 hexdigest (with
length of 32 chars) value as base topic name. md5 used to have guaranteed the
same value for the same seed in different threads or even nodes.

Change-Id: Icd674d92c94be21ed9ac037fa6c5bd132b00340e

commit_message:
Reduce global CONF usage in zmq driver

Reduced usage of global CONF object. Implemented a decorator for lazy
options registration. Each essence uses config options is independent
from others. Registered two options groups for zmq driver.

Since this patch the tests require `eventlet`. `eventlet` added to
test-requirements-py3.txt.

Change-Id: I2905cb288617052bf1c039aef000aeeee6468e15
Closes-Bug: #1373382

I like this change, but it wouldn't fix https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1338732.  The problem in the bug is where the server sends a reply before the client creates the reply queue.

If you are going to set the timeout when creating the queue, consider also setting it in NotifyPublisher.reconnect (impl_rabbit.py around line 414).

This needs a unit test"}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-07-29 19:07:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Noel Idea of this patch is that queue is not deleted when client disconnects. It's kept for expiration time even without consumers so client can later reconnect to same queue. This allows not losing messages at all.

>unit test

IMHO it's not possible to provide a unit test for this this our unit tests are using different transport (inmemory). This can only be covered in functional tests (I've started to work in this direction)"}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-29 19:27:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The queue will not exist at all if rabbit dies and restarts.  

1. client declares reply queue
2. client sends message
3. rabbit dies and restarts, queue is gone
4. server reconnects, gets message, sends reply to exchange without queue, message is lost
5. client reconnects, waits forever for message.'}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-07-29 19:28:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ah.. you are right.. we have a bit different configuration since we are using rabbit in HA mode.. in our case queues are not deleted.

This means that this fix is good for HA but not good for single rabbit'}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-29 19:29:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Noel, reply queue is created before message is sent to the server. So the situation you describe is impossible. Maybe it looked that way because reply queue was deleted right after it was created, but this patch fixes it'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-07-29 21:52:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Also I assume that there is a RabbitMQ cluster and not all nodes die simultaneously. If 100% of RabbitMQ nodes die/restart then message can be lost. The only solution exist is to have both queues and messages durable. Otherwise even if the server redeclares queue it may be deleted again (and the message in that queue) before client awakes from sleep after connection loss. Having durable queues may be a good idea but it deserves a dedicated commit'}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-29 22:01:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Stan, in our case we run a single rabbitmq, no cluster, so when that server dies after the client sends the reply, the reply queues are gone.  The failure scenario above is quite reproducible where the reply queue has not been created when the server publishes the reply.'}, {'account_id': 7125, 'date': '2014-07-30 09:21:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-07-30 09:36:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Noel,
reply_q is created here: https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/stable/icehouse/oslo/messaging/_drivers/amqpdriver.py#L379

and the message is sent after that place here:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/stable/icehouse/oslo/messaging/_drivers/amqpdriver.py#L391-L400

both things happen in single thread, so no possible race conditions. Do you see how the message can be sent before queue is created?

But, the reply_q was marked as auto-delete. That mean that RabbitMQ will delete it as soon as number of consumers gets above zero and then drops to zero.

Client starts to listen for reply_q here:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.messaging/blob/stable/icehouse/oslo/messaging/_drivers/amqpdriver.py#L403
just after the message is sent. Even if somehow the message was sent before reply_q was declared it is very unlikely that server will receive, process and reply before client code advances to the next line of python code (and that you will be able to reproduce it at wish). 

But when client starts listening for reply_q number of consumers becomes > 0. That means that if failure condition happens at this moment consumer number will drop to zero and queue will be deleted. (If rabbitMQ itself get restarted it will also be deleted even with this fix. Durable queues is the only possible solution to this, assuming you don not have RabbitMQ cluster). So by the time server receives (or done processing) request reply_q has gone. With this fix it will remain for additional hour.

As for NotifyPublisher.reconnect:
my patch changes anything only if the original intention was to create queue with auto-delete. In reconnect auto-delete flag is never set. So if we assume this code to be working now there is nothing to change here. On the other hand all consumers either declare queue with auto-delete or allow to control this with config file. This means that if consumer was to declare this queue with auto-delete and reconnect always ignores this flag we will get PRECONDITION FAILED from RabbitMQ. In another words this code is already broken and need to be fixed in separate commit'}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-30 16:18:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Here's what happens:

1. client creates receive_q
2. client sends message
3. rabbit dies and restarts.  We run a single instance of rabbbit because we've had problems with HA rabbit.
4. rabbit restarts somewhere else.  The receive_q is now gone
5. client loses connection to rabbit, waits 1 sec to reconnect
6. server reconnects to rabbit, gets message, declares exchange for receive_q, but does not redeclare the receive queue
7. server sends reply to exchange, but since there's no receive queue, the message is lost
8. client finally reconnects to rabbit, redeclares receive queue, but never gets reply

Hope that's clear, it happens for us repeatably.  To reproduce:
1. run single instance of rabbit
2. kill rabbit
3. do a vm migration
4. goto 2 until you see "Timed out waiting for message".  

See https://gist.github.com/noelbk/f8476952809dac8a295c for a log of this in action'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-07-30 16:24:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Then its a different problem that is also valid. There is only one possible solution to what you've described - having both queues and messages be marked as durable in addition to my fix. I'm okay with this fix, but it needs different commit. Making server redeclare the queue would not help with what you're saying because rabbit may restart right after server sends response back but before client receives it"}, {'account_id': 8772, 'date': '2014-07-30 19:07:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:
