Personally I think the conceptual clarity of configuration and how it affects failover is eroding, though this specific change plays only a tiny part in that.

Everytime you restart a server, the old reply queue and exchange will remain for an hour. Any fanout old consumer queue will also be left abandoned which is more problematic as it will still be bound to the shared exchange, so will still gather messages.

Personally I think a more holistic approach to meeting reliability expectations on failover is advisable. Lots of little tweaks to address different symptoms will in my view make the system ever harder to understand.'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-08-19 10:46:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Gordon, so what is wrong with that? The queue will remain for additional hour so no messages will be lost and the whole system can recover. The price is negligible. The worst thing that can happen is queue will not be deleted for one extra hour. And this requires just a tiny change in the code.

Also note that this patch solves real-life HA problem that was observed by QA team many times and that broke the entire OpenStack after controller node crash. 

But if you know better solution please suggest'}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-19 10:58:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

If the queue is abandoned i.e. the process that declared it has gone and the new process started has created a new queue in its place, then preserving the queue does no good.

Where that queue is the subscription queue for a 'fanout consumer', it will be bound to the fanout topic. That means it will accumulate any new messages that are broadcast to all the fanout consumers on the topic and these messages will never be consumed. Whether that causes significant problems depends on the volume of messages (and the number of such orphaned queues). However it is in my view clearly a 'bug', and fixing one issue by introducing another is not ideal, even if the new issue is considered less severe."}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:15:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Correct me if I'm wrong, but AFAIK no two different services can create queue with the same name. So if abandoned queue still receiving messages that means those messages belong to the service that is currently doesn't work. So as soon as the service start again those messages will be processed and thats a good thing. 

Now I understand the issue with fanout. In theory it is possible for queue to be filled with with messages that are already processed by another instances or no longer relevant. But I think this need to be addressed by setting TTL on the messages instead of relying on queue being deleted. And that deserves dedicated commit.

Using auto-delete queues for RPC is fundamentally wrong because they deleted as soon as all consumers disappear. That means that any temporary network failure (even for a fraction of second) may cause lose of all queues and their messages.

I do agree that introducing one problem to solve another is not a good thing. But I don't agree this is a real problem (but the one it solves is surely a real). And what is more important this is only bad when there is a better solution. Otherwise I'd like to have a small problem instead of big one. So again, if you know a better solution please suggest otherwise it is not constructive"}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:47:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The issue with fanout is that each subscriber has its own queue. If you allow stale queue to remain bound, they will accumulate messages without there ever being a consumer for them. It isn't really an issue of the message no longer being relevant or not.

Yes, you could certainly set a ttl on messages sent to the fanout consumers that would limit the build up. Personally I think that is merely working around the problem. When you have workarounds around workarounds the system gets hard to understand. Personally I think that is what is happening.

I disagree entirely that using auto-delete queues for RPC is wrong. I think it is a very good choice. Temporary failures for RPC are in my view better handled by resending the request. It is more robust and more scalable. That of course is merely my opinion.

If the whole of openstack really fails because a reply queue named with a uuid has been autodeleted, then I think openstack is far too fragile.

I believe it would be better to clarify the expectations around RPC calls when a failure occurs. There are many different symptoms that can occur depending on the exact timing. There seems to be no unambiguous statement on what the result should be - i.e. whether the caller should be prepared to handle timeouts and retry or whether the library is responsible for doing that. Addressing various different symptoms with fixes that themselves introduce new (even if minor) issues, is in my opinion the wrong approach. That is intended as constructive feedback. If you don't think it is, you are free to ignore since my -1 is in no way binding."}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:53:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Gordon, I agree with your point. I believe, RPC should be strictly standardized (are there any rfc for it?) Please join the discussion http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-July/041524.html.

Sadly, we still need a w/a unless we have an rfc for RPC which will adress all the aforementioned'}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:54:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

One suggestion for keeping your suggested approach but minimising the scope would be to set the queue option only for direct subscribers, i.e. only for reply queues.

In that case I would also suggest that 1 hour is much longer than needed. Is anything really going to wait up to an hour for a response to an RPC call before timing out and retrying or considering it failed?'}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-19 12:01:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-08-19 12:03:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I do agree that OpenStack services should handle messaging failures and that deletion of queues should not affect OpenStack stability in long running. Unfortunately this is not the case now and its beyond my ability to fix. So yes, this is a workaround that we can do and the only alternative is to leave as is, let it hang. Once OpenStack becomes less fragile we can switch back to auto-delete queues if you'd like.

As for having x-expires only for reply queues - if someone can fail because it never receives response it will fail as well if the server never receives (and thus never answer) original request because its queue was deleted

Anyway, I've got your concerns, you understand my point. Lets wait for other opinions"}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-08-19 12:05:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8784, 'date': '2014-08-19 12:10:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Stan, re "As for having x-expires only for reply queues - if someone can fail because it never receives response it will fail as well if the server never receives (and thus never answer) original request because its queue was deleted" - requests are sent to topic consumers and the autodeletability (as well as the durability) of those can already be controlled through config. For those I don't think there is any need to have a timeout on the queue, but if there is it would be better to make it configurable at least.

(A request may not have even reached the queue at the point of failover and thus be lost even if the queue remains. This is less likely as the window is smaller, but still needs to be considered for a robust solution)

However as you say, lets allow others to chime in :-)'}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2014-08-19 12:18:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In my code x-expires is set only if caller intentions were to set auto-delete. So if auto-delete was turned off in config x-expires wouldn't be used too. commit_message:
Auto-delete queues were deleted on RabbitMQ failover

When RPC client starts listening to reply queue and got disconnected from RabbitMQ,
reply queue got deleted because it was marked as auto-delete and no more consumers
were present.

This fix replaces auto-delete with queue 1H expiration. So clients have
up to an hour to reconnect to RaqbbitMQ prior to server's reply gets lost

Change-Id: Ic1a20c309ff90618f715f4034847e6e159c486e8
Closes-Bug: #1349301

commit_message:
Add API for introspecting VMDKs

This change adds vmdk.py and test_vmdk.py(correspoing unit tests)
to oslo/vmware and tests/ respectively.
vmdk.py has a class API which has the following methods
introspecting VMDKs(monolithicSparse, monolithicFlat,
streamOptimized):

    *get_adapter_type
    *get_disk_type
    *get_virtual_size

Change-Id: I2e9966790b7d0dd9b669aa0c10bea2f3a2c459f7

I'm not sure the pattern Neutron is following of running the RPC and API threads in the same service and then starting multiple workers for each is really what we want to support with this, so I don't know if we want to fix this or change the way Neutron manages services. Are there any other examples of applications using the class the way Neutron does?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-29 21:02:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Traverse children list to check if any worker stop

Currently Neutron server spawns two green threads for api and rpc
job. In _wait_child, both green threads get pid of the stopped
worker from os.waitpid, but if the pid is not in the green thread's
children list, the stopped worker is not restarted.

Considering this two green threads are in the same process, api
green thread may get a pid belonging to a worker forked by rpc
green thread and will not restart the worker. We need to traverse
the children list of each green thread in _wait_child to ensure
stopped worker can be properly recognized.

Change-Id: I056235b11f3e239a8a7e78a507e002978a306b8c
Closes-Bug: #1384580

and python3. Based on a patch in Debian/Ubuntu
by Thomas Goirand.

[{'created': '2015-01-06 03:05:19.000000000', 'message': 'Make tox use develop mode

Currently running tox fails on a system where pbr isn't installed in
the base-environment.  This is because "python setup.py sdist" isn't
run in the virtualenv and thus the package gets built as
"UNKNOWN-0.0.0.zip" and subsequently fails.

Running tox in develop mode seems to be the standard way things are
done in other parts of the projects.

Also copy in some other standard settings; install_command using pip
(which requires minversion = 1.6) and handing testr args

Change-Id: I9017d0bbc0e606a28b70ca20fff3f58068fc062d
'}]
commit_message:
Make tox use develop mode

Currently running tox fails on a system where pbr isn't installed in
the base-environment.  This is because "python setup.py sdist" isn't
run in the virtualenv and thus the package gets built as
"UNKNOWN-0.0.0.zip" and subsequently fails.

Running tox in develop mode seems to be the standard way things are
done in other parts of the projects.

Also copy in some other standard settings; install_command using pip
(which requires minversion = 1.6) and handing testr args

Change-Id: I9017d0bbc0e606a28b70ca20fff3f58068fc062d

commit_message:
Prevent a UnicodeDecodeError in the s3token middleware

Mixing "str" and "unicode" can lead to a UnicodeDecodeError. We encode unicode
values before using them with text strings.

The bug occurs if the URL contains a non-ASCII character in the tenant id:
"hého" in "/v1/AUTH_cfa/c/hého" ("/v1/AUTH_cfa/c/h\xc3\xa9ho" in UTF-8) for
example.

The bug occurs on Python 2 in s3_token.py because the tenant id is retrieved
from identity_info['access']['token']['tenant'] and identity_info comes from
resp.json().

The problem is that in Python, the JSON decoder always create Unicode strings.
Example in Python 2:

>>> json.loads('{"key": "value"}') {u'key': u'value'}

There is no issue in Python 3, since all text strings are Unicode.

Change-Id: Ib7fdf60f8369ea9546fcd92f1ac385c777478d10
Closes-Bug: #1428706

commit_message:
Update rccut and rcdelivery to match Kilo process

For Kilo we switched to using stable/* instead of proposed/* as the
pre-release branch. Update scripts to match that.

We also stop waiting for tarballs to be built and compare them to
previous branch tarballs -- we can't rely on that test given how much
time it takes to get branch tarballs generated those days.

Change-Id: I46f069ccb5e5a6baa9c768f7d5e1c7d1237e6546

commit_message:
Add option to format release notes for email

Add an option to generate an email message body suitable to be passed to
sendmail or msmtp so it can be sent directly without having to be copied
into another email program.

Change-Id: I166ca5d8f31ddd97d5298ff9f8f5c44037dfe4b7

commit_message:
Reduce Transactions Usage in Mech driver

Bond transactions together to reduce the number of
OVSDB transactions

Change-Id: Icb545b2ae2c31e550c42f1b8bd8fc8bf075a06ff
Closes-Bug: #1443461

commit_message:
Reduce the number of OVSDB transactions

This patch aggregate value creating/settings to
one command in order to reduce OVSDB transactions
and avoid un-needed re-searches for each value setting

Change-Id: Ib96b3f0991092949fa4c0363183ed4951a92c9d9

commit_message:
ClusterPolicy module for bindings btw the two objects

This is an object to represent the bindings between clusters and
policies. An explicit object representation hopefully can help easy
runtime operation of its fields.

Change-Id: I3b1d07089efd933ac21b0b38a7372b0013a23fe4

commit_message:
Don't short circuit when projects fails to clone

This change adds a check to propose_update.sh,
avoiding it to go into fatal error when a project
fails to clone.

Just report the incident and move onto the next
project.

Change-Id: Ib22403f1bd27070b8121a9d79bb95cae409dbe7d

I believe this is the wrong direction for largeops. 

Largeops was a hack put into place to handle the regressions we saw in nova db usage. It never really fit into Tempest, but was added because that's all the tools we had.

We should instead figure out what lower level tests can expose the issues we are concerned about.

I think Largeops should be deleted by the end of kilo."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-12-02 20:18:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I agree large-ops was a hack. Now that we are starting to use functional testing jobs, perhaps this is better suited as a neutron functional test?'}, {'account_id': 8576, 'date': '2014-12-02 20:39:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Sean, Joe,
Thanks for the review.
Neutron aren't planning on adding VM creation to their tests in the foreseeable future. Not sure if Nova are going to test Neutron network in theirs, but this also won't be in this cycle, and working on this test I've already found a bug in the Nova/Neutron notifications system.
Also, since this is proper Nova/Neutron integration test I fail to see how it could live anywhere else.
Though I agree that "large-ops" is more of a stress test. maybe a post-merge / periodic one. I have some ideas about re factoring this.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-12-04 14:43:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I am glad to hear working on this caught some bugs. You do make a good point that this does test nova+neutron integration. Still not sure where this should live though. nova and neutron are much more tightly coupled then say nova + keystone. making this sort of thing complex to split into two sets of tests.

How does neutron expect to do functional or stress testing without using nova?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-08 05:14:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Adds scenario for network-large-ops

* Spins up multiple instances in one nova call as a regular user.
* VMs are connected to network (unlike test_large_ops)
* Verifies instances are ACTIVE.
* Assigns Floating IP and verifies connectivity to each instance.

Pulls logic for bulk_servers_create from test_large_ops to manager

Adds network-large-ops to tox.ini

Changes required from devstack:

In nova.conf:
quota_instances = -1
quota_cores = -1
quota_ram = -1
quota_floating_ips = -1
quota_fixed_ips = -1
quota_metadata_items = -1
quota_injected_files = -1
quota_injected_file_path_bytes = -1
quota_security_groups = -1
quota_security_group_rules = -1
quota_key_pairs = -1

In neutron.conf:
quota_network = -1
quota_subnet = -1
quota_port = -1
quota_security_group = -1
quota_security_group_rule = -1
quota_vip = -1
quota_pool = -1
quota_member = -1
quota_health_monitors = -1
quota_router = -1
quota_floatingip = -1

In tempest.conf
tenant_network_mask_bit should allow for $large_ops_number IP addresses in
tenant

Change-Id: I5593393dc30262b4b28f4274695d604825d29383

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-24 11:27:57.000000000', 'message': 'Downcase /etc/hosts entries

The entries received from Heat are based on Heat names of
OS::Nova::Server resources, which can contain uppercase letters. However
the hostnames set by Nova are lowercase. This can make the actual
hostname differ from entries in /etc/hosts, which can make the output of
`hostname -f` differ from `facter fqdn`, which can cause failed Puppet
runs.

This patch makes sure that the /etc/hosts entries that Heat adds are
lowercase.

Change-Id: Iec5b6450c5730c081c8f2ca4d6c9786b956c87d5
Partial-Bug: #1447497
'}]
commit_message:
Downcase /etc/hosts entries

The entries received from Heat are based on Heat names of
OS::Nova::Server resources, which can contain uppercase letters. However
the hostnames set by Nova are lowercase. This can make the actual
hostname differ from entries in /etc/hosts, which can make the output of
`hostname -f` differ from `facter fqdn`, which can cause failed Puppet
runs.

This patch makes sure that the /etc/hosts entries that Heat adds are
lowercase.

Change-Id: Iec5b6450c5730c081c8f2ca4d6c9786b956c87d5
Partial-Bug: #1447497

commit_message:
Validate cluster attributes

Add validation for cluster attributes. Do it so that it doesn't break
compatibility with current tests. Validate regexpes if they are provided.

Change-Id: I9c1fc04dab45aecf3e32615172654d11844df7c3
Closes-Bug: #1447407

commit_message:
Rename keystoneclient-federation to saml2

Saml2 authentication plugins were initially extracted to the federation
repository, however we don't want to lump all these plugins together as
they may have very different dependencies and jobs.

Rename repo to more accurately reflect contents.

Related governance change is Ia25e14a6afa939590ebba3a91973ceee4a8eaee2

Change-Id: Ie23f0c3a1f3e0a65baabe3dbd19091908da1aba2

commit_message:
Enable tenant/user specific instance filtering

This patch enables tenant and user specific filtering.
Prior to this, one could not filter list of servers on
tenant or user basis.
For example -
nova list --tenant <tenant_id> [--user <user_id>]
This was not giving desirable output.
This patch removes this limitation.
Note in above that currently python-client does not implement
"--user" argument. I will add a patch for that also.
Thus one can filter out servers tenant and user basis.
If you are not passing user info then current context
user will be entertained.
Similarly, If you are not passing tenant info,
this will entertain current context tenant.
Closes-Bug: #1398329
Author: Mh Raies raiesmh08@gmail.com

(cherry picked from commit cf209713dff8bc84e0f251f9f2dc2a2e6fcf0ae0)

Co-Authored-By: Michal Jura mjura@suse.com
Change-Id: I53ca239395b538bc103a8e5cefc728142a034f20

commit_message:
Add experimental Identity v3 jobs to devstack

Identity API v3 jobs use the auth_version=v3
setting in Tempest, which uses v3 auth tokens.

In order to make Devstack use only tokens v3 and
Identity API v3, some work still need to be done.

This change enables an experimental check on
Devstack to be used on the incoming Devstack
patches.

Partially-implements: bp/keystone-v3-jobs

Change-Id: Iba9ed29cbc726c2abdb0a99ec789af949169a920

commit_message:
FirstApp: Move source directory up, rename top-level dir

For the RST guides, we do not need doc/source, since doc is always
empty. Use source directly.

This syncs the setup used here with openstack-manuals.

Rename top-level from openstack-firstapp to firstapp, there's no need
for the long name in this repo.

Change-Id: If4e11a4f90d580876865348e0d88b92cec4b6659

commit_message:
Fix RabbitMQ OCF stop/start actions

W/o this fix, rabbitMQ OCF may hang on the stop or start
as it ignores the stop/wait commands exit code. This is an
issue as it prevents rabbit node from joining the cluster.

The solution is to report generic failure, if corresponding
commands timed out:
* Fix stop_server_process() timeout command exit code check.
* Fix try_to_start_rmq_app() timeout command exit code check.

Closes-bug: #1446190

Change-Id: I8a0ccdde88cbb4c8545427f5bd6bdca6856a4687
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 1b553e823effcd14d59f42ec36852339d709e7a4)

commit_message:
Fix RabbitMQ OCF stop/start actions

W/o this fix, rabbitMQ OCF may hang on the stop or start
as it ignores the stop/wait commands exit code. This is an
issue as it prevents rabbit node from joining the cluster.

The solution is to report generic failure, if corresponding
commands timed out:
* Fix stop_server_process() timeout command exit code check.
* Fix try_to_start_rmq_app() timeout command exit code check

Closes-bug: #1446190

Change-Id: I8a0ccdde88cbb4c8545427f5bd6bdca6856a4687
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 1b553e823effcd14d59f42ec36852339d709e7a4)

commit_message:
Chnage the default IP_VERSION to 4

DevStack has been set to dual stack by default in Kilo+.
Therefore all tests are failing. Reverting to V4
for integration tests till we fix the templates.

Change-Id: I4a9e4b40d0a1d8dc4231b4331eef82508d0f22a8

commit_message:
Puppet/Beaker: drop puppet-{gnocchi,tuskar}

For now, Gnocchi and Tuskar are not packaged in Ubuntu so there is no
way to test the modules with Beaker Rspec.
Until we have the packages, let's drop the useless jobs from the CI.

Change-Id: I895e58d0ea1e8e2c61086a1e0024c411e31a9e63

commit_message:
Remove mention of anti-virus scan

Index page mentioned binary assets were being
scanned for viruses - this is not being practiced
consistently, and should not be mentioned. Removing
for now, and will eventually be replaced with
legal disclaimer indicating downloader is responsible
for determining safety and suitability of all assets.

Change-Id: I78693a6fe94e9173840e688e5b737c0cb78ab950

commit_message:
Added field 'data' to cluster-policy bindings table

This table will be used by a policy to record per-binding data. Sample
use case include -- a policy that requires monitoring records alarm
resource IDs here for their lifecycle management; a load-balancing
policy records the resource of LB pool resource created.

Change-Id: I0ba28bb5cecbc95e5a33032dff9ce30618249ec5

commit_message:
Allow changing project-id and user-id by alarm-threshold-update

Ceilometer alarm-threshold-update should support updating
project-id and user-id, but the update function was silently
ignoring changes of these options.

Change-Id: I33231bff44b90f3c58e5ef1646349b6dc63a3ce7
Closes-Bug: 1395932

For the method level logs, change the log level from INFO to
DEBUG for consistency and to also conform to the OpenStack logging
policy.

Change-Id: Ie8b621e8799da1b1dde600857c8f27b276826bea
Implements: MNP-119

commit_message:
Add image name support when create a baymodel

Currently, if we create a baymodel and pass an image name as parameter,
an image not found exception would be raised.

This patch add image name support when create a baymodel

Closes-Bug: #1448952

Change-Id: If8b41eacccf0880908dafebb3e86e374399c0bef

commit_message:
Minor tweaking to cluster update flow

This tweak tried avoid using new temp variables for no good. It also
moves the intialization 'inputs' dict closer to where it is used.

Change-Id: I0ca5af71a1a5d8d44943de23532daebe3549cf44

Ok dokie; I'm not sure where this will be useful, but that shouldn't stop it from being used :-P"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-02-05 14:56:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

The implementation looks OK, but I'm not sure about the use case. Do you have an example of where it would be OK to add a new required positional or keyword argument to an existing API?"}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2015-02-09 01:51:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

So obviously you can't add a new required positional argument, that's going to break compatibility regardless. 

I've found this useful a lot in keystoneclient. For example, when swapping people over to using adapters and such i'm taking the Client.__init__ function which for most clients is 20 or so parameters, which i want to abstract as **kwargs and push over to adapter. I'm breaking compatibility because you could have specified all those 20 variables positionally. 

Same thing where i've wanted to push Sessions as the default way to build a client. I want it to make sense to pass the session as the first positional argument - and in 99% of cases it would be fine for me to rearrange the order because everyone uses those parameters as kwargs anyway - but i can't be sure of that. 

Retrospectively this stuff is almost impossible to enforce but it means we ensure some flexibility going foward and push some best practice of how to call our apis out to users."}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2015-03-08 22:50:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

maybe debtcollector is a better place to propose this?'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-03-09 02:06:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Import positional decorator used by keystoneclient

The positional decorator provides a way to ensure that certain arguments
are passed as kwargs when specified. This provides some great advantages
in maintaining backwards compatibility as you can add new positional
arguments in front of existing keyword arguments, or rearrange existing
keyword arguments.

Change-Id: I7f5b998c73884e590ab2e290fcdd84c006e1452c

commit_message:
Adds Neutron networking to compose/README

Previously, the readme only contained instructions for configuring
nova networking. This patch adds instructions for downloading and
creating a cirros Glance image and neutron networking.

Change-Id: I4aba32baf3e270bb9aa16fde068d99223e75ef66

commit_message:
Import subprocess in cache devstack element

Change fd9c80208c00021a49df6907973bbbb3fa242069 inadvertently
removed the subprocess import from 55-cache-devstack-repos even
though it was used in a function defined within that element, unlike
in its snapshot prep script counterpart. Readd it so that this
element works again.

Change-Id: I954a1e7e99af96b08e0a59e99e513902731fd773

I am really not a fan of relying on PATH to find privileged executables.  I know this is DevStack and security is not at the top of out priority list, but PATH in sudo and rootwrap is just a bad practice and I'd rather not use it in a place where people will point to it and say "but DevStack does it".

IIRC rootwrap itself actually encourages this practice and I've called it out in a couple of places, maybe its time to submit the changes to get rid of the practice?'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-04-27 10:44:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm also not convinced that this is best done in devstack if it's done at all. The neutron review kept saying 'only needed for devstack', but that's not true. This is needed for source based installs on any Debian / Ubuntu system.

We need to stop putting *all* the logic of source install into devstack, the source trees themselves need to support the idea that they might be source installed."}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2015-04-27 13:10:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The goal here is to facilitate use of the neutron HA feature in terms of root wrap configuratoin. We have tried a few approaches so far:
  -- add local filter in l3.filters
  -- add /usr/local/bin to exec_dirs in neutron/etc/neutron/rootwrap.conf, which will then be copied to /etc/neutron/rootwrap.conf during ./stack.sh
  -- modify lib/neutron-legacy to add /usr/local/bin to exec_dirs  in /etc/neutron/rootwrap.conf 

I see that everyone has a good point preferring one to the others. Sean has a good point indicating that all the exes are installed in /usr/local/bin on Ubuntu/Debian. So the second approach seems to be reasonable.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-04-30 17:21:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-30 17:21:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Add /usr/local/bin to exec_dirs in rootwrap.conf

devstack installs neutron utilities into /usr/local/bin such as
neutron-keepalived-state-change and neutron-ns-metadata-proxy.
In stead of adding individual filters to allow them to run from that
directory, this patch adds /usr/local/bin into exec_dirs.

Please also refer to I3abd1c173121dc8abb5738d1879db8ac9a98b690 for
discussion on the approach to fix the bug.

Change-Id: Iade8b5b09bb53018485c85f8372fb94dbc2ad2da
Closes-Bug: 1435971

commit_message:
Revised cluster-update implementation

We now allow min_size and max_size to be updated. So, the code must
be generic and flexible to support different combinations of update
parameters. This patch revised the cluster-update api implementation
which will be followed by a revision at cluster-action level.

Change-Id: I3718c1ead517ad719a34d83ffc0c4a4c6a49b5fb

commit_message:
Add min_size and max_size properties to Cluster

Two new properties are added to cluster: min_size and max_size.
This patch provides related support from client side. Now user
can specify the min and max size of cluster when creating it.

Change-Id: I72869259993ec8a8697eba45c12bf6ba9d408292
Implements: blueprint add-size-limitation-properties-to-cluster

commit_message:
Nic bonding support for SRIOV ports

We want to enchance Nova to be able to bond SR-IOV ports to provide HA.
First of all we need to create a mechanism which can land VFs to the different
PFs if it's needed. Next step will be create a Neutron call to hold number of
VFs we need for it.

Change-Id: I7e790b2dc33a170008283ff6bc2e6e17b09bbddb

commit_message:
Add a new libvirt volume driver for Huawei SDSHypervisor

Add a new volume driver in nova/virt/libvirt/volume.py file to realize
attach/detach volume to qemu-kvm instance, and realize abstract volume dirver
methods:
* connect_volume
* disconnect_volume

Change-Id: I1d18fda62b77c5f46eed174fc0699d8bbe14fe92
Blueprint: huawei-sdshypervisor-volume-driver

commit_message:
Fix issues in User CRUD section

The user CRUD section had several issues.

 - CRUD wasn't defined
 - public_api is a literal string from the config file
 - The pipelines are now defined in keystone-paste.ini
 - The default pipeline has changed, stats_monitoring and xml_body
   don't exist anymore
 - tokens are invalidated in every token persistence backend

These are corrected.

Change-Id: I0620e8543d76220e2263ace2145e2b4eb0529b30

- gate-nova-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/54/133254/4/check/gate-nova-specs-docs/0a8f03e/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 06s
- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/54/133254/4/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/09cbdd6 : SUCCESS in 1m 29s'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-11-13 20:34:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I would like to address the topic of should nova support PXE in general first (same as for https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130451/)'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-18 11:16:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)

@Joe why do you think Nova shouldn't support PXE boot.  IMHO there is no question that this is a useful feature.

NB, Nova doesn't even need to provide the PXE boot server features itself. It could already exist on the LAN that Nova-network/neutron has been plumbed into, or the user can setup a bunch of their own VMs and one of them can provide PXE services to the VMs."}, {'account_id': 11905, 'date': '2014-11-18 13:05:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

As I wrote in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130451/
We could also discuss in a nova meeting, if you prefer.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-11-18 22:57:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Daniel, the main reason is because of feature creep. Don't we have enough ways to boot an instance from a specific image?"}, {'account_id': 11905, 'date': '2014-11-19 07:16:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Joe, there are some telecommunication systems that work and boot by PXE because it is based on a known and shared specification (several RFCs deal with it).
 
In these cases there are a lot of cons to adapt their booting procedure to Openstack way.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-19 09:57:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I don't think "feature creep" is really a compelling argument against this. People already do PXE boot with Nova by using a stub ISO image from glance which then does PXE to pull down the real image. This is rather sucky approach to force our users into using. Adding support for network boot to Nova isn't going to impose a significant burden on our ongoing development, and is going to give the users a more effective way to achieve a use case they're having to hack around currently.

IOW I think this is a worthwhile thing to do for Nova users.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-11-19 17:47:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I am with Joe here. Nova is not a rest api for libvirt, and other hypervisors, its meant to provide a useful high level cloud abstraction.

That being said, PXE could be useful, if only for testing PXE. But there are less intrusive ways, such as booting up an image that does PXE booting. Thats what the XenAPI driver supports today.

Regardless of that discussion, I still think there are some details I think need to be worked through here. The API seems a little too loosely defined.

I wonder if there is a simpler approach that solves the problems you are trying to fix?'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-11-19 17:49:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hmm, see we already have some boot order, I see now.

I guess I don't see why this is such a useful feature given the impact on the REST API. So it would be good to describe that better I think."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-19 18:03:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

Requiring booting up an image that does PXE booting is not a real solution. It is a limited functionality hack to work around the lack of a solution. It doesn't let you express device order preference when booting the VM, without having to create custom PXE ISO for each boot order. That is not practical, particularly when you want to be able to ultimately choose booting off assign PCI devices."}, {'account_id': 11905, 'date': '2014-11-19 21:27:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11905, 'date': '2014-11-19 21:53:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I think that some users need pxe and need to choose the booting vnic. They merely use a workaround (empty disk) to do it. Anyway I think a good idea could be to submit this feature to TelcoWorkingGroup in order to have their opinion. Any thought?'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-11-20 00:37:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I feel rather strongly that we should make sure that a boot order based scheme will work with XenServer's support for PXE booting.

That said, I also feel like this is a change that carries more questions than are currently answered here. Tying the booting of an instance to any arbitrary network seems bad to me, especially for a network with no DHCP server or support. I also think it'd be weird to boot an instance that tries to PXE boot from a public network/interface. Is this supported only on neutron-based systems? I assume the goal is to allow tenants to set up their own PXE server and clients, which also implies characteristics of the network that would allow that.

I guess my gut feeling is that this is lacking a cloudy use case (i.e. one that isn't based on consolidation of legacy workloads to virt de jour). If we're going to do it, I think more verbiage in this spec about the Xen support, network implications, etc needs to be fleshed out. However, unless there is a compelling reason, I'd rather see us not take on an extra way to boot instances, especially since there is a way to do this now with an iPXE image."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-20 10:44:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14055, 'date': '2014-11-20 10:49:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I would like to add some background information. This proposal of boot device selection stems from a request for PXE booting support in OpenStack made by a telco equipment maker. While migrating from their bare metal application to cloud technology, they require this functionality. If it will not be supported, they are forced to use a work around or add this feature on their own as customization. Therefore I think we should consider that there are strong use cases which justify the implementation of this feature. But, of course, also the technical discussion needs to reach an agreement in order to integrate it nicely into the OpenStack architecture.'}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2014-11-20 20:17:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

We have certainly had people at CERN requesting this feature. An image to do the PXE is not the cleanest solution.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2014-11-25 22:45:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Seems we already have one project in OpenStack, Ironic, that does a bunch with PXE booting. In fact, it also has the various stuff needed to integrate this with Neutron and everything.

Now, obviously Ironic does not provide the same things Nova provides, but it does show that we already have in the ecosystem a thing which turns nova boot requests into PXE operations.

Perhaps, in addition to having the broader conversation of whether this is a thing Nova wants to provide for VMs in general, we should also think about how we can avoid having two implementations of nova->pxe in OpenStack.'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-11-26 11:46:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Monty Taylor: I don't know very well Ironic project, but for what I understood it  makes use of PXE to deploy on bare metal nodes an image retrieved from Glance. This obviously doesn't have much sense in a VM controlled by Nova, since if we want an image stored in Glance, we can use it directly with an image boot.
What we really want here is only to enable the network booting for instances in Nova, so an instance can retrieve the image from a TFTP server (which can be another instance in Nova). The logic to provide the image to the booting instance will be in the TFTP server rather than in OpenStack.

I think anyway that Ironic can benefit from this feature as an alternative to have to fetch an image from glance to the Ironic conductor and then using the Ironic conductor as TFTP server for the bare metal nodes. 
In fact enabling network booting in nova will allow to specify as TFTP server another machine in the tenant for Ironic too."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-11-26 20:54:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

So just a generic question around what features of nova/openstack will and will not work with the addition of this functionality? Seeing that I didn't see it mentioned in the spec I drew up a little list that seems like it should belong inside this spec.

- ConfigDrive network specification (pxebooting would seem to make this feature useless as the instance would need to use DHCP)?

- Glance snapshots (since now the pxeboot server would be providing the image)?

- Cinder boot from volume (what's the point since the pxeboot server will be providing the image)?

- Any nova setups not using DHCP (?)

In general I'd rather have that kind of analysis done and placed in this spec; so that it's clear that the results/functionality that this introduces will have outcomes on the larger integration with other projects that need to be considered. 

Overall I'm not so sure about adding this (especially the usecase around network booting); in part because of that analysis needed above and due to the fact that if this is turned out it has side-effects in other systems (and in general side-effects in the funtionality of what nova and integrated projects can provide) that deployers need to be aware of. It sort of feels hacky in general and although I understand the legacy 'desire' to have this it generally feels like it's not pushing the 'bar' but is just accommodating folks that have said legacy systems (for better or worse). As for what is the right thing to do I don't know which is why this is just my feeling on supporting this; but I'd almost rather have said folks spend effort on getting off there legacy systems instead of adding a feature to nova (that impacts other projects) that now nova has to support in the long term (thus making there be less incentive to move off said legacy systems in the first place).

With regard to the usecase: 'further use case deals with a user that wants to select the boot disk out of several disks which are connected to the vm/instance'; this one seems more reasonable as it doesn't have as big of a impact on the functionality of nova and projects that integrate with it."}, {'account_id': 6772, 'date': '2014-11-26 23:28:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-11-27 16:04:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Joshua Harlow:
 
Considering the list of not working features you proposed I will try to clarify my point of view for each item in it.

- ConfigDrive network specification: as you said the instance booting from network will require DHCP enabled, but this is true for the network on which the pxe traffic flows; an instance can have more than one network attached and the pxe booting doesn't have any requirement for additional network interfaces (i.e. DHCP can be disabled on those), so the ConfigDrive can still be useful for an instance that uses pxe boot.

- Glance snapshots: you are right saying that Glance snapshot don't work with a PXE boot (not out of the box anyway). Anyway rather than a cons I see this issue like a reason to support our proposal. Let me explain: today there are yet people using pxe booting in OpenStack loading in Glance an iPXE bootable iso image. In this situation taking a snapshot of the istance don't lead to any error, anyway the created snapshot is not bootable. It is easy to see that using a workaround - like the bootable iso iPXE image in Glance - can lead to problems for users. If the feature is supported in OpenStack this problem can at least be handled disabling snapshots for pxe booted image and providing the user with a warning message. I thank you to have raised this point and I agree it should be underlined in the specification.

- Cinder boot from volume: well this is an alternative booting option, but in the same tenant can cohabit instances booting from volume or from network. Moreover for the same instance it will be possible a boot order priority that involve both network and volume. I don't understand well why this should be an issue. 

- Any nova setups not using DHCP: As I said before an instance can be attached at same time to networks with DHCP enabled or disabled, so even in scenarios in which the DHCP has to be disabled it is possible to think of a network dedicated only to pxe booting. Or it is possible to configure a DHCP server that will answer only to to pxe requests and not to other DHCP. I don't really see any limitations on this point."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-11-27 20:08:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Seems like moving the pros/cons into the spec RST itself would be useful now that you've done a little analysis (which is good!)"}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-12-10 02:29:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Patchset four is quite old, and there are requests to update the spec in review comments. Is this proposal abandoned?

I'd be more than happy to discuss this at a nova meeting if we think that would unblock the conversation."}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-11 16:52:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-11 17:02:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

New patch to address some comments. 

@Daniel Berrange: you expressed interest in enabling boot priority for PCI devices too. 
In libvirt these are handled in <hostdev> section where it is possible to add a <boot order> element exactly how it happens for <disk> and <interface>.
Anyway in OpenStack there is not an API to handle them at instance boot time (like for disks and network interfaces), they are managed via flavor or via port creation (am I right?)
If this is the case I am not sure if we should deal with boot order for PCI devices in this specification. Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-11 17:06:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/54/133254/5/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/bef3e2b : SUCCESS in 1m 29s'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-12-11 17:09:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Some types of network port are backed by a SRIOV PCI device assigned to the guest. So although from the public API pov it is still a network device, from the internal libvirt POV it will be a <hostdev> or a <interface> element.  I wouldn't worry about the use of PCI device assignment for non-network devices at this stage. Just bear in mind it will be something we might consider adding later."}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-12-12 02:50:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Have we explored adding PXE support as a backend to glance as an option? That would leave us with the same level of functionality proposed here, but with more nova features working.'}, {'account_id': 11905, 'date': '2014-12-12 09:18:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I think we could split this blueprint in two: the first blueprint   will introduce per-device boot element only for the disk devices providing a clearer and full control over booting order , the second one will deal with the network devices and will depend on the first one.'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-12 09:22:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Michael Still

With PXE support as a backend to glance do you mean using glance as DHCP/TFTP server?'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-12-12 09:52:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

@mikal doing PXE in Glance cannot possibly offer the same functionality as outlined here. If the user needs to PXE boot over a NIC that is an assigned PCI host device there is no way for glance to even get acess to that PCI device. Similarly there's no way to get the fine grained ordering of boot priority across the disk, net, hostdev devices in a guest."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-12-12 13:20:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-12 14:22:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-12-12 15:18:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

+1 for just doing this via glance. As I previously said, I don't think that just giving control over the boot order is sufficient modeling for something as complex as PXE booting from any network interface."}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-12 15:33:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Dan Smith: the boot from network is a feature already available in libvirt. This specification doesn't propose to implement anything new about pxe booting, only to enable in Openstack something that works in libvirt."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-12-12 18:48:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

After further discussion on the ML about the PXE bootcase, I don't think its one we should support"}, {'account_id': 11002, 'date': '2014-12-17 12:23:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Added some thoughts on a possible another use case, i.e. migration of legacy systems delivered on ISO disks into the cloud. I think this BP could cover that use case as well by allowing boot precedence configuration between cdrom and disk devices.'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-17 12:34:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Since most of the objections regard the network boot part, would it be preferable to split the blueprint and start to work only on the boot order for sources yet supported in OpenStack?'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-12-19 12:31:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

A nice alternative suggestion I heard is the ability to boot from config drive, and have that include ipxe, so you can configure ipxe to boot from the correct interface.

I like how that is less likely to "muddy" up our API.'}, {'account_id': 13071, 'date': '2014-12-19 12:53:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@John Garbutt: I didn't heard in specific about this possibility, anyway I don't see much difference to have a PXE iso loaded in Glance, how can you assure the boot starts on the correct interface (if you were referring to the fact we proposed a way to select a specific network interface when more are present)?"}, {'account_id': 11002, 'date': '2014-12-19 14:31:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

Just to point out, the key problem for OpenSAF-based NFV applications is to keep under control which network(s) can be used for PXE booting and which ones mustn't. NFV applications are interfacing with many networks, some of them are internal "trusted" networks, others are external "untrusted" ones.  It is a hard security requirement that the application must not boot from any untrusted external network under any circumstances as that would be considered as a major security risk. This must be secured even in the case if the application-owned boot servers are not accessible on the trusted internal network for a while. Consequently, just giving a boot precedence to vNICs interfacing with internal networks is not enough to resolve this sechole.

Using iPXE from Glance is a working solution but keeps this sechole open as long as iPXE has no clue on which vNIC is connected to which network. When migrating legacy telco architectures into Openstack, we could use a workaround to create Neutron ports with pre-specified MAC addresses and restrict iPXE to use only the white-listed addresses. However, it is quite difficult to combine this solution with application scaling requirements. 

Blocking PXE traffic on external ports via firewall rules is not a working option with existing Openstack configuration facilities.

The original security problem could be resolved either by using the cloud API to control the white-listed boot interfaces, or by exposing the network connectivity information towards an application-defined boot loader, e.g. to a customized iPXE build, loaded from Glance. In the latter case, the connectivity information should allow iPXE to correlate attached vNICs with network tags like trusted/untrusted or symbolic names. If config drive contents can be extended with such information, that could also provide an equivalently good solution, and that is something that would be useful for the NFV applications themselves too.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-01-28 19:02:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-2

This is too late for kilo, lets look at getting this sorted at the L summit, or a meetup, or similar. Bringing this to the nova-meeting might also make sense.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-01-28 23:58:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Moving to -1, to make it easy to move this to L'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-05-04 02:16:45.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Please update this spec for Liberty if you're still interested in pursuing it."}]

commit_message:
Spec boot order for instance

This specification proposes a way to define a boot order for a
instance across devices, whether disks or network interfaces.
Spec updated according to some comments

APIImpact

Implements: blueprint boot-order-for-instance

Change-Id: I6abdb2b50b38b241db30b3ff655b84579ec5af46

commit_message:
Remove links attribute from pod show

The links attribute in pod show wraps the table formatting making it
difficult to read. The links attribute is generally not relevant to the
user and does not need to be displayed.

Change-Id: I0737ae6eb9422464c60030dd60fcbe65744c948a
Closes-Bug: 1450392

commit_message:
Add retry to lvm delete

Seems we have another issue related to lvm and
snapshots, but this time it's on the delete side.

We used a simple retry mechanism for snapshot create
here:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/149360/8

I'm hesitant to just add another retry without looking
at dm issues, but this should address the problem
temporarily and give us a chance to collect some
data on the issue.

Change-Id: I37607a09e2f9af6f2f32ddfaa8567400541e533a
Closes-Bug: #1450110

commit_message:
Mount with -o nouuid for XFS base images

This change uses blkid to identify the fs type during redhat-common
extract-image. The image is mounted with -o nouuid for redhat/rhel
images that have XFS filesystems.

This is required when building images from the same base image
as the host VM to avoid "Filesystem has duplicate UUID" mount
failures.

Change-Id: I066289fbb27733a5a555242a0e2c363d58dd27d0
Closes-Bug: 1443706

commit_message:
Add min_adjustment_step property to ScalingPolicy

Adds `min_adjustment_step` property to ScalingPolicy
resource. It represents the minimum number of resources
that are added or removed when AutoScaling group scales
up or down. This can be used only when specifying value
`percent_change_in_capacity` for `adjustment_type` property.

Change-Id: Ia8976e52047ab47245566487ce1872a8890bcff2
Closes-Bug: #1447913

commit_message:
Drop tox from test-requirements.txt

test-reqs.xt gets installed by tox, so the chicken is before the egg.
This blocks devstack when run with strict requirements, as tox isn't
listed in global-requirements.txt.

Change-Id: I780fffa1e8a830b598ac2cee963c79ccad154e6a

commit_message:
Fake out sleeps in unit tests

Just a minor cleanup, had a few tests that were doing sleeps
(or looping calls for those that prefer it) that were being
executed to test timeouts in the unit tests.  No value in
actually *waiting* for these, so this patch just mocks them
out so we still test the procedure but don't actually have
to wait.

This shaves about 30 seconds or so off of the unit test run,
not a huge deal, but every little bit helps IMO.

Also noticed a LOG.debug message in the test_extensions file
that wasn't picked up in other cleanup work so I removed that
debug log call as well.

Change-Id: I415ac75816e8a0f4c48c61b23391df1a9a016d62

commit_message:
Add JsonPayloadSerializer serializer

JsonPayloadSerializer exists in a several OpenStack projects such as
cinder, ironic, magnum, nova, trove so there is a sense to keep it in
oslo.messaging to avoid of code duplication.

Change-Id: I77a6e5e3e717b0afcf17b6200d5b8ff5db6e3262

commit_message:
Functional tests for listing resources and templates

- convert the magnum command line in post_test_hook.sh
  into test cases
- delete key-pair after functional tests are run
- adding test for creating/deleting baymodels
- adding test for creating/deleting bays
- Remove dummy test (tests/functional/test_magnum.py)
templates.

Partially Implements blueprint: improve-functional-tests
Change-Id: I2937f2659a29e0f9b411c10b080db79bc46ce910

commit_message:
Specify Nova API versions clearly

Now Nova v2.1 API is CURRENT and v2 is SUPPORTED.
We have a plan to switch /v2 endpoint to v2.1 API on Nova side, and
we need to test both APIs on the gate.
This patch makes check-dg-tempest-dsvm-full v2 API specific clearly
and changes the configuration way based on the Depends-On patch.

Change-Id: I9ebcde2135d31f6ebefd1017cf8de3b07f497fca
Depends-On: Iba57eab5947c3e9112e8e6d12b8212e964a8d8ca

Reorganize exceptions

I hope this to be the base exceptions for all clients. Reorganize them
to make sense, remove some we don't use and make use of them.

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package.

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I950f1afb1b4600dfc1f38d1a7d9322f240f444a6

commit_message:
Update vendor support to reflect v2 non-task

Vexxhost and RunAbove both support v2 of glance, but do not require
the task interface. Update the erroneous information. Also, there are
two additional regions for Rackspace that we did not list. We don't
list the Rackspace LON region because it does not work like the others
and we do not know how to support it.

Change-Id: Ib155d00d1d6bf7b2e5bcf4b868c268561e198611

commit_message:
Add hacking check for str and unicode in exceptions

One of the comments we are frequently having to make
on reviews is with regards to the use of str() or
unicode() on exceptions.  This hacking check pulled
from Nova will catch this problem earlier and avoid
conflicting comments being made in reviews.

Change-Id: I09eaf7b066f3e29733e6cbe16b2997edb6bc5e23

commit_message:
Don't install redhat-lsb-core in prepare_node

We don't need it for anything other than detecting whether or not we
should update the sources.list file. Except that's obviously not
something we should do on systems with yum

Remove the call and defer it to install_puppet where it's also
installed.

Change-Id: Ie22aeac1e4c731e7ab61514cb4982c8c35c482e6

commit_message:
Override PXE options via Glance property

The proposal presents the work required to allow PXE boot an image using
a specific kernel command line for that image.

Change-Id: I9371394eb1fd90ed52bf8de82e6f53a9c135f244

Would like some others to have a look at this before I +2 it, but it LGTM and I can't think of anything addressed here. 

I'm not an expert on glance interactions, but I'm also curious if this could allow for an escalation of privileges; currently if you're on the instance deployed by pxe deploy driver, you can't modify the kernel command line. With this change, depending on how the properties are locked down in Glance, you would be able to.

I think this is an overall good thing, but I'd like someone who uses the pxe driver more to weigh in."}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-01-05 09:20:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Chris,

Regarding the landed spec, that offers no backward compatibility with images that use the glance properties.  As such, I don't see a conflict with this specification.  It does raise a question how the kernel command line property will be passed to Ironic if http:// is used as an image source.

I really am not certain, as it is unclear to me how the image source makes its way into the registered list of images Ironic is aware of.  I need more details about the implementation.  I have added vdok as a reviewer on this patch."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-01-05 23:09:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Steven, here is implementation of the spec you mentioned - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/136741/

There are some image_source properties pulled from glance now, such as kernel_id and ramdisk_id for PXE, checksum for IPA and ilo_boot_iso for iLO. That implementation is not approved and could change, but for now all the properties required should be put into instance_info, the same could be done in this case. If there will be too many different properties to read (4 now, 5 with suggested kernel_cmdline) it maybe better to introduce something like image_properties dictionary inside instance_info.

So, I think it will work fine :)'}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2015-01-06 21:05:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Override boot options via glance property

The current PXE boot kernel command line is global in nature.  Instead,
allow individual images to override the global kernel command line with
glance image properites.

Change-Id: Ia1add8a1b27a8e7aefca8c6fd186335fc8cea6a8

commit_message:
Failed to discovery when iscsi multipath and CHAP both enabled

Storage server may be configured to protect target discovering phase with CHAP
authentication, in this case existing discovery command will be failed.
The authentication properties are:
    "discovery.sendtargets.auth.authmethod",
    "discovery.sendtargets.auth.username",
    "discovery.sendtargets.auth.password"
Cinder Storage driver need to send discovery auth properties in this case,
and the properties are:
    iscsi_properties['discovery_auth_method']
    iscsi_properties['discovery_auth_username']
    iscsi_properties['discovery_auth_password']

(cherry picked from commit 45227bbbfd06d16e85e973e14ee8c30e267e8b42)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/libvirt/test_volume.py

Closes-Bug: #1367189
Change-Id: Ic70426d7d0fd8126879840f05341731ed92d6392

commit_message:
Type conflict in trusted_filter.py using attestation_port default value

When trusted filter (nova/nova/scheduler/filters/trusted_filter.py)
in nova scheduler is running with default value of attestation_port:

default='8443'

method _do_request() in AttestationService class has this line:

action_url = "https://%s:%d%s/%s" % (self.host,
self.port, self.api_url, action_url)

It is easy to see that default type of attestation_port is string.
But in action_url self.port is required as integer (%d).
It leads to conflict.

This change provides more tests than is required only to cover this bug
fix. This cases are testing AttestationService _do_request() method
using different status_codes and different texts returned by mocked
request method.

(cherry picked from commit fdcf358eaeef6edb5c8d2dcc94f906a22882544a)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/scheduler/filters/test_trusted_filters.py

Tests aren't in tests/unit/.

Use jsonutils from nova.openstack.common instead of oslo.utils.

Closes-Bug: #1381468
Change-Id: I1ad57b5bd1986360416948fd00dec22456dc29a7

commit_message:
Moves trusted filter unit tests into own file

Breaks out trusted filter unit tests into their own file. In the
process, we remove all DB accesses from the unit tests and uncruft the
unit tests with mock.

(cherry picked from commit f388ac5e8f5338fd2c4817de11b7436f85036bc6)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/scheduler/test_host_filters.py

Backporting this patch for
change I1ad57b5bd1986360416948fd00dec22456dc29a7 .

Added nova/tests/scheduler/filters/__init__.py, which is created by a
patch we aren't pulling in.

Updated test to use timeutils from nova.openstack.common instead of
oslo.utils, as the filter hasn't been updated yet to use oslo.utils.

Change-Id: Ic895b06a9f6a224f153f12ca5ab54dc8be931f13

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Sets *DataRoot paths for instances

Sets the path for the instance's ConfigurationDataRoot,
LogDataRoot, SnapshotDataRoot, SuspendDataRoot and
SwapFileDataRoot for vmutilsv2 instances and
ExternalDataRoot and SnapshotDataRoot for vmutils

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V dynamic memory issue with vNUMA

vNUMA and dynamic memory are mutually exclusive, so the former
needs to be disabled for instances where dynamic memory is enabled.

Change-Id: Ic730c294ffc89925076688a44adf2594c7f6712b
Closes-Bug: #1305897
(cherry picked from commit 1b20a40aa18c0f248256f2ae36e328b4a7cc20c1)

commit_message:
Make puppet-ceph unit tests compliant with Puppet4

- Bump rspec-puppet to 2.1.0 includine Puppet 4.0 support [1].
- Bump puppetlabs-apache to 1.4.1
- Bump puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1

[1] https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/commits/v2.1.0

Change-Id: I95f9d837281727c51e9c813996f73f4f0e9e44f5
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Create subnet object in sync port

Avoid losing port segmentation_id data in case sync port is
called before sync_router.
Create subnet object and update data on sync router

Change-Id: If5342ab8dada650e623e37080f01ca309d5463e2

to the controller.
